INSERT INTO `charities` VALUES (26,'The Food Project','10 Lewis Street','Lincoln','MA',1773,'http://thefoodproject.org/','04-3262532','<p>Our mission&nbsp;is to grow a thoughtful and productive community of youth and adults from diverse backgrounds who work together to build a sustainable food system. We produce healthy food for residents of the city and suburbs and provide youth leadership opportunities. Most importantly, we strive to inspire and support others to create change in their own communities.</p>','<p>Each year, we work with over 150 teens and thousands of volunteers to farm on 31 acres in Lincoln, seven acres in Beverly, two and a half acres in Boston, and one acre in Lynn, Mass. We grow over a quarter-million pounds of food without chemical fertilizers or pesticides and donate thousands of pounds of produce to local hunger relief organizations.&nbsp; We sell the remainder of our produce through&nbsp;community supported agriculture&nbsp;(CSA) farm shares and&nbsp;farmers&rsquo; markets. Locally, we promote access to fresh, affordable produce by building raised-bed gardens for residents and organizations, offering garden-based educational programming, and providing opportunities for people to use SNAP/EBT benefits to purchase fresh food. &nbsp;<br /><br />The Food Project also works as a resource center for organizations and individuals worldwide. We provide uniquecapacity building&nbsp;for organizations and educators who learn from The Food Project&rsquo;s expertise through materials, youth training, and professional development opportunities. Even projects completely unrelated to farming can draw on our methods for building inspired, diverse, and productive youth communities.<br /><br />The Food Project has been the subject of a number of&nbsp;research papers, some of which we have been able to make available online. We have also made and been the subject of a number of&nbsp;videos&nbsp;available for your viewing. A&nbsp;short history&nbsp;of The Food Project explains how we got where we are today.</p>','http://www.facebook.com/thefoodproject?fref=ts',9,0,0,'','http://youtu.be/pjHd1wML9tY','2013-03-12 16:24:22','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'the-food-project',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,'The Greater Boston Food Bank','70 South Bay Avenue','Boston','MA',2118,'http://www.gbfb.org/','04-2717782','<p>The Greater Boston Food Bank\'s mission is to end hunger in eastern Massachusetts. Our objective is to distribute enough food to provide at least one meal a day to those in need.</p>','<p>The Greater Boston Food Bank (GBFB) is the largest hunger-relief organization in New England and among the largest food banks in the country. Last year, we distributed almost 41 million pounds of food, enough to provide healthy meals to as many as 545,000 people. We are committed to increasing our food distribution in 2013 to provide at least ONE MEAL A DAY to every person in need in eastern Massachusetts.</p>\r\n<p>GBFB acquires food through food industry product donations, food drives and financial contributions that enable us to purchase additional high nutrient quality food. We also benefit from the&nbsp;generosity of over 18,000 volunteers&nbsp;annually who help to sort and distribute donated food products.</p>\r\n<p>GBFB works to acquire, store, organize and distribute food through local food pantries, community meal programs, homeless and residential shelters, youth programs, senior centers, and day-care centers embedded in communities throughout the nine counties of eastern Massachusetts.&nbsp;GBFB&rsquo;s food assistance locator&nbsp;provides an easy way for people in need to find help nearby. GBFB also&nbsp;distributes food directly to those in need through dedicated programs&nbsp;that serve particularly vulnerable groups, such as seniors and children.</p>\r\n<p>Since 2009, GBFB has operated out of a state-of-the-art, 117,000 square foot food distribution facility, the Yawkey Distribution Center, located in the Newmarket section of Boston.</p>\r\n<p>The Greater Boston Food Bank is a member of Feeding America, the nation\'s largest hunger-relief organization.</p>','',8,0,0,'@Gr8BosFoodBank','http://www.facebook.com/gr8bosfoodbank','2013-03-12 17:09:57','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'the-greater-boston-food-bank',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(42,'United Way of Hampshire County','71 King Street P.O Box 123','Northampton','MA',1060,'http://unitedwayhampshirecounty.org/','04-2104792','<p>The United Way of Hampshire County is about advancing the common good. It is about sustaining and strengthening a network of local agencies prepared to respond to our neighbors in need.</p>','<p>The United Way of Hampshire County is about advancing the common good. It is about sustaining and strengthening a network of local agencies prepared to respond to our neighbors in need. United Way invests in opportunities that create a better life for all. We focus campaign investments in three areas that offer some of the basic building blocks for a good life - a good start for children and youth, health and safety for all and resources that promote economic security. And, as the lives of those in need improve, our entire community benefits.</p>\r\n<p>Your support means giving a voice to an abused child in the courtroom, offering a low-income child the joy of summer camp or allowing a youth-at-risk to spend an afternoon with a trusted role model.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Your support means refuge from violence for a mother and her children, getting people back on their feet after a disaster or making visible those often overlooked.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Your support means putting food on the table of a working family, shelter for a night or a lifetime, or a helping hand to navigate the day-to-day complexities of life.</p>','',1,0,0,'','http://www.facebook.com/unitedwayofhampshirecounty','2013-03-12 17:31:40','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'united-way-of-hampshire-county',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(48,'HESSCO Elder Services','One Merchant Street','Sharon','MA',2067,'http://www.hessco.org','','<p>At HESSCO Elder Services we&rsquo;ve dedicated ourselves to finding solutions to help those over sixty take full advantage of their later years.<br /><br />Our goal is to make it easier for older individuals and their families to access a comprehensive system of health and supportive services.</p>','<p>Information and Referral Program supports elders and their families, as well as persons who are disabled, by answering questions and connecting callers to appropriate services to meet their needs. The Information and Referral Specialist actively listens to each caller\'s concerns and responds, advocates and matches the resources to each individual call or will research the issue and respons in a timely manner.&nbsp;<br /><br />Cost of service to client:&nbsp;Free to everyone, regardless of age or income level.<br /><br />Calls to HESSCO Elder Services&rsquo; main number are transferred to Information and Referral, where a specialist talks with the caller and assesses the needs of the elder, person who is disabled or caregiver concerned. The Information and Referral Specialist has access to an extensive network of experienced professionals to help answer questions and a large database of area resources to aid in referrals.<br /><br />The Information and Referral Program allows callers to receive simple, understandable answers to aging-related questions. Because the program specialist discusses their specific situation with them, each caller receives information tailored to their specific needs. All discussions are confidential.<br /><br />Frequently asked questions<br /><br />Q: I know my mom needs help. What kind of services do you offer?<br />A: HESSCO Elder Services offers a broad range of services, and we have connections to a great many more service providers in the extended community. To help make the decisions less confusing, we talk with you to evaluate what type of services are needed, and then connect you with the programs that can help, either within HESSCO Elder Services or at another agency.<br /><br />Q: What are the requirements to get services for an elder?<br />A: These requirements vary depending on the service. Some are free to everyone, and others have income guidelines. Those with income guidelines can range from a voluntary co-payment to payments on a sliding-fee scale, to a percentage of your monthly income. We explain all your options when you call, and we can help you assess your eligibility for reduced-fee programs.<br /><br />Q: Do you have any information on assisted living communities?<br />A: We have a list, but we don&rsquo;t make recommendations. We can send you a booklet listing the assisted living communities in your area, and you can call or visit them and make your choice accordingly.<br /><br />Q: How do I get help paying for heating fuel?<br />A: We can help you apply for fuel assistance through Self Help Inc. and the South Middlesex Opportunity Council (SMOC). We also have information on other fuel assistance programs.<br /><br />Q: The elder I care for needs a wheelchair (or hearing aid, handicapped accessible van, etc.). How do I pay for this?<br />A: We can help you apply for a loan through the Easter Seals loan program for medical equipment. We also have information on companies and organizations that provide medical equipment.<br /><br />Q: Can you recommend doctors specializing in geriatrics, podiatry, or psychiatry?<br />A: An information and referral specialist will research the availability of these and other specialists in your area. While we can&rsquo;t provide recommendations, we can give you the information that will help you make an educated decision.<br /><br />Q: How can I find a hairdresser who will come to my home?<br />A: Our information and referral department keeps an updated list of hairdressers who do home visits.<br /><br />Q: How can I get adaptive telephone equipment?<br />A: We have applications for different programs that provide telephone equipment adapted for the needs of people with disabilities. We can help you choose the program that&rsquo;s right for you and fill out the application forms.<br /><br />Client snapshot<br /><br />A stroke had left Mrs. Arroyo paralyzed on her left side, needing to use a wheelchair, and with limited mobility. She had improved sufficiently to be released from a nursing home into her daughter Maria&rsquo;s care. While she was happy to have her mother back at home, Maria worked full-time and would not be available to assist her during the day.<br /><br />Information and Referral received a call about Mrs. Arroyo only a few days before she was released from the nursing home. The nursing home&rsquo;s social worker had arranged for a visiting nurse, physical therapist, and home health aide to visit Mrs. Arroyo in her home, but funds for those visits would end after a few weeks. Mrs. Arroyo would still need personal care after the visits ended, but she and her daughter were not sure where to turn.<br /><br />The Information and Referral Specialist arranged to have hot meals delivered to Mrs. Arroyo at home, starting immediately upon her return. The specialist answered questions about the types of services available, many of which Maria and her mother had not been aware existed. The Information and Referral Specialist then arranged for an intake and assessment specialist to visit Mrs. Arroyo and Maria to speak with them about providing services that would help Mrs. Arroyo stay at home. This mix of immediate information and rapid referrals made Mrs. Arroyo&rsquo;s homecoming smooth and relieved Maria of worry.</p>','',5,0,0,'@HESSCO','http://www.facebook.com/HESSCO?ref=nf#','2013-03-12 18:03:52','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'hessco-elder-services',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(50,'Homes for Our Troops','6 Main Street','Taunton','MA',2780,'http://www.homesforourtroops.org/','54-2143612','<p>Homes for Our Troops, founded in 2004, is strongly committed to helping those who have selflessly given to their country and have returned home with serious disabilities and injuries. We assist severely injured servicemen and women and their immediate families by raising donations of money, building materials and professional labor and then coordinating the process of building a new home or adapting an existing home for handicapped accessibility. The finished home is then given to the veteran. All services provided by Homes for Our Troops are at no cost to the veterans we serve.</p>','<p>We are Homes for Our Troops, a national non-profit, non-partisan 501(c)(3) organization founded in 2004. We are strongly committed to helping those who have selflessly given to our country and have returned home with serious injuries since September 11, 2001. It is our duty and our honor to assist severely injured Veterans and their immediate families by raising donations of money, building materials and professional labor and to coordinate the process of building a home that provides maximum freedom of movement and the ability to live more independently.</p>','http://youtu.be/BLlDzsGk2M4',8,0,0,'@HomesForOurTrps','http://www.facebook.com/homesforourtroops','2013-03-12 18:09:04','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'homes-for-our-troops',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(51,'Horizons for Homeless Children','1705 Columbus Avenue','Roxbury','MA',2119,'http://www.horizonsforhomelesschildren.org/','22-2915188','<p>Our mission is to improve the lives of young homeless children in Massachusetts and help their families succeed by providing high-quality early education, opportunities for play, and comprehensive family support services. To support our mission, we also advocate on behalf of young children, train educators and human services providers, and provide research on the impact of early education on homeless children.</p>','<p>Horizons for Homeless Children was founded in 1988 as an independent organization dedicated exclusively to serving young homeless children and their families. Horizons for Homeless Children touches the lives of more than 2,200 young homeless children each week in Massachusetts through Playspaces (educational and recreational spaces) in shelters and 175 children through its three Community Children\'s Centers, Boston\'s only comprehensive, full-time early education and childcare centers specifically for homeless children. In addition to direct service, we advocate on behalf of young homeless children and their families with policy makers and provide training and technical assistance to related service providers.</p>\r\n<p>What happens in early childhood can matter for a lifetime. In young children, stress resulting from major trauma such as extreme poverty and homelessness, can weaken the developing brain and can lead to lifelong problems. By providing effective&nbsp;early education programs,&nbsp;the consequences of early trauma can be prevented and society can ensure that all children are prepared for school and life success.</p>\r\n<p>Homeless children often experience chronic stress and trauma from frequent moves; inconsistent relationships; lack of places to play; and witnessing domestic violence and substance abuse. This stress and trauma is emotionally and cognitively damaging to them.</p>\r\n<p>Effective&nbsp;early education programs&nbsp;can improve the outcomes for young homeless children and ensure success later in life. These programs, such as Horizons for Homeless Children, build supportive, dependable relationships; are staffed with qualified teachers and social workers; and emphasize language and cognitive development. Research has shown that investments in quality early education programs in the early years of a child&rsquo;s development also generate the greatest societal returns including reduced crime, welfare, and specialized educational services.</p>\r\n<p>Child and family homelessness is an escalating crisis. Accurate data is difficult to obtain and validate due to the transitional and often &ldquo;invisible&rdquo; nature of the population</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','http://youtu.be/q7DaNMI6zTA',9,0,1,'@HHCTweets','http://www.facebook.com/horizonsforhomelesschildren?ref=ts','2013-03-12 19:53:07','2013-09-04 18:55:34',NULL,'horizons-for-homeless-children',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62,'Jumpstart','308 Congress Street 6th Floor','Boston','MA',2210,'http://www.jstart.org/','04-3262046','<p>Jumpstart is a national early education organization working toward the day every child in America enters school prepared to succeed. Jumpstart delivers a research-based and cost-effective program by training college students and community volunteers to serve preschool-age children in low-income neighborhoods. Through a proven curriculum, these children develop the language and literacy skills they need to be ready for school, setting them on a path for lifelong success.&nbsp;</p>','<p>Jumpstart is the only national supplemental program&nbsp;that leverages the power of community and adult-child relationships to build the key language and literacy skills children need to take on the world.</p>\r\n<p>From an early age, children should be exposed to activities that encourage a love of language and learning and a sense of wonder about the world. For far too many children from low-income communities, though, this never happens. And once children from low-income backgrounds start behind, research shows that they&rsquo;re very likely to stay behind.&nbsp;<br /><br />But it doesn&rsquo;t have to be this way. And that&rsquo;s where Jumpstart comes in.</p>\r\n<p>Since 1993, Jumpstart has trained 28,000 college students and community volunteers to transform the lives of 50,000 preschool children nationwide. These Corps members help children cultivate a life-long love for language and learning and ultimately provide a foundation for future success.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Core values are only meaningful when they&rsquo;re lived out each and every day.</p>\r\n<p>From our inspiring Corps members to our dedicated staff and our impressive leadership team, we believe in honoring our core values by working in service of children. We recognize we&rsquo;re stronger and more effective in preparing America&rsquo;s children when we do it together, so we hold each other mutually accountable for living out these core values at the individual and organizational levels.</p>','http://youtu.be/F3vf8_zO98E',3,0,0,'@Jumpstartkids','http://www.facebook.com/Jumpstartkids','2013-03-12 20:57:33','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'jumpstart',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67,'Make-A-Wish Foundation of Massachusetts and Rhode Island','One Bulfinch Place','Boston','MA',2114,'http://www.massri.wish.org/','22-2867371','<p>Make-A-Wish&reg; Massachusetts and Rhode Island grants wishes for children with life-threatening medical conditions to enrich the human experience with hope, strength, and joy.<br /><br /> According to information from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, approximately 500 children in Massachusetts and Rhode Island are newly diagnosed with life-threatening medical conditions every year. Our vision is to grant wishes for every medically eligible child annually.</p>','<p>The joy began in 1987, when Make-A-Wish Massachusetts and Rhode Island fulfilled its very first wish: a family trip to York Beach for a little girl with Niemann-Pick Disease. Since that first inspired wish, the organization has served over 5,000 children in Massachusetts and over 1,000 children in Rhode Island.<br /><br /> We have grown from granting a single wish in our first year to granting 390 wishes in during our 2011 fiscal year. Our mission extends from the Berkshires to Cape Cod, from Providence to Newport, through three offices in two states.<br /><br /> Our organization honors our community&rsquo;s generosity by exercising the utmost fiscal responsibility. According to our most recent audit, 80 percent of every dollar donated is directed to children&rsquo;s wishes. We keep administrative costs low by leveraging the skills of 600+ volunteers who help coordinate wishes.</p>','',5,0,0,'@makeawish','http://www.facebook.com/MassRIWish','2013-03-12 21:15:12','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'make-a-wish-foundation-of-massachusetts-and-rhode-island',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(72,'Massachusetts Coalition for the Homeless','15 Bubier Street','Lynn','MA',1901,'http://www.mahomeless.org/','22-2599662','<p>The mission of the Massachusetts Coalition for the Homeless is to eradicate homelessness from the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.&nbsp;</p>','<p>The Coalition&rsquo;s early intervention and direct service work, along with our commitment to finding long-term solutions to homelessness, have allowed us to develop innovative programming and realistic solutions to ending homelessness. Over the past decade, the Coalition&rsquo;s approach has increasingly focused on homelessness prevention.&nbsp; Prevention is cost effective, supports the ability for households to maintain economic stability, and gives children the stability needed to receive a solid education. The Coalition integrates prevention resources at the places where people are already receiving services, thus providing seamless and timely access to prevention resources.&nbsp; &nbsp;We also run a furniture bank that has helped thousands of households transitioning out of homelessness obtain the essentials they need to make their new house a home.&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />The agency has worked to embed homelessness prevention resources in community health centers, public schools, and in our in-home early intervention programs.&nbsp; The prevention programs have had impressive results with helping at-risk households to retain or secure housing. A pioneer in arena of homelessness prevention, the Coalition is called upon by both state agencies and school districts to share our knowledge and expertise.<br />&nbsp;<br />The Coalition recognizes the importance of sharing our knowledge and expertise; to that end, we offer comprehensive trainings to providers working with low income households and to lay people who want to do something to help those in need.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />Our comprehensive approach allows us to address the root causes of homelessness, while also ensuring that services are provided to those in immediate need.&nbsp;</p>','http://youtu.be/yJ07-DfJBv8',8,0,0,'@MAHomeless','https://www.facebook.com/macoalitionforthehomeless','2013-03-12 21:30:18','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'massachusetts-coalition-for-the-homeless',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(79,'All Hands Volunteers','PO Box 546','Carlisle','MA',1741,'http://hands.org/','20-3414952','<p>To provide immediate, effective and sustainable support to communities in need by harnessing the energy and commitment of dedicated volunteers.</p>','<p>In 2005, our founder David Campbell flew to Thailand after seeing the devastating effects of the 2004 South East Asian tsunami. He traveled there to see what he could do to help. After learning that spontaneous unaffiliated volunteers were being turned down by aid organizations, David and a few friends organized a group with the sole purpose of connecting those who wanted to help with those who needed it. After raising more than $100,000, they began rebuilding five villages.<br /><br /> Recognizing the power of true volunteerism, David co-founded All Hands Volunteers in response to Hurricane Katrina. It is with this history that we serve communities in need all across the globe, with an emphasis on flexibility, agility and open mindedness.</p>','',1,0,0,'@AllHands','http://www.facebook.com/hands.org','2013-03-16 12:44:07','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'all-hands-volunteers',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(86,'Animal Rescue League of Boston','10 Chandler Street','Boston','MA',2116,'http://home.arlboston.org/','04-2103714','<p>The Animal Rescue League is a non-profit organization dedicated to rescuing domesticated animals and wildlife from suffering, cruelty, abandonment, and neglect. Since 1899 we have advocated the philosophy of our founder, Anna Harris Smith, that &ldquo;Kindness Uplifts the World&rdquo;.</p>','<p>I want to tell you how excited and honored I am to have been named the President of the Animal Rescue League of Boston. As the eighth president of an organization with such a long and proud history, I am inspired to be part of a mission focused on enriching the humanity of our society.</p>\r\n<p>Over these past few weeks, I&rsquo;ve had heartfelt conversations with League employees, some of whom have spent 20, 30 and even over 40 years providing care and comfort to the animals we rescue and shelter. Their dedication to the ARL of Boston&rsquo;s mission is amazing.</p>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve also met dozens of volunteers including members of the Board and Overseers who give an extraordinary amount of time, treasure and talent to the League including directly caring for the animals we shelter. We simply could not do what we do without this tremendous outpouring of support.</p>\r\n<p>I look forward to working with staff and volunteers as we strengthen this incredible institution so that it continues to provide humane care and protection to domestic animals and wildlife for years to come.</p>\r\n<p>Mary Nee, President</p>','',1,0,0,'@ARLBoston','http://www.facebook.com/AnimalRescueLeagueofBoston?fref=ts','2013-03-16 13:51:41','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'animal-rescue-league-of-boston',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(88,'Artists For Humanity','100 West 2nd. Street','South Boston','MA',2127,'http://www.afhboston.org/','04-3138434','<p>Founded in 1991, Artists For Humanity&rsquo;s mission is to bridge economic, racial and social divisions by providing under-resourced youth with the keys to self-sufficiency through paid employment in the arts.</p>','<p>Youth and mentors collaborate on creative projects, many specifically commissioned by clients. In the process, young artists develop entrepreneurial skills, and introduce audiences to the voice, vision and virtuosity of today&rsquo;s youth. Artists For Humanity has produced fine art and creative products for most of Boston&rsquo;s largest firms and organizations, and &ndash; despite the challenging economy &ndash; earned over $800,000 in sales last year.</p>\r\n<p>The AFH model has received national recognition and has been studied extensively as an exemplar of effective mentorship, youth empowerment and social entrepreneurship. Their model has been disseminated internationally to organizations that utilize their framework of respect, relationships, and responsibility to empower young people in their communities.</p>\r\n<p>In 2004, AFH completed its headquarters, the Platinum LEED Certified Artists For Humanity EpiCenter. Built to the highest levels of sustainability of the U.S. Green Building Council, it serves to inform its youth of issues of environmental stewardship, and serves as an inspiration and backdrop for their creativity. Named one of the &ldquo;Top Ten Green Buildings&rdquo; in the country, and one of the &ldquo;5 Most Beautiful Buildings in Boston&rdquo; it provides a fitting venue for perhaps the largest permanent display of youth-created fine art in the nation.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BP8-l2RukI4&list=UU37hSpY4mtXd-Ie8fs6rbvA&index=9',3,1,1,'@AFHBoston','http://www.facebook.com/ArtistsForHumanity?ref=ts','2013-03-16 13:58:04','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'artists-for-humanity',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(102,'The Center for Teen Empowerment','384 Warren Street','Roxbury','MA',2119,'http://teenempowerment.org/','04-3091002','<p>The mission of the Center for Teen Empowerment is to empower youth and adults as agents of individual, institutional, and social change.</p>','<p>The&nbsp;Teen Empowerment Model&nbsp;is the product of decades of thoughtful experience in changing the values, beliefs, and behaviors of youth and adults, making institutions more effective, and developing mechanisms for people of all ages to work productively together toward achieving important goals. The model\'s developer, Stanley Pollack, began his career in 1973 as a street outreach worker for the city of Somerville, Massachusetts, and the basic components of the model were created over the next eight years in Somerville. From 1982 to 1992, Stanley built a successful consulting practice, implementing the model in communities throughout Massachusetts. In July 1992, with the support of the Boston Foundation and the Hayden and Riley Foundations, he founded The Center for Teen Empowerment, Inc. in order to demonstrate both the power of the TE Model to generate solutions to difficult problems that confront urban communities and the model\'s potential applications in a wide range of social service and educational settings.</p>\r\n<p>The Center began work in Boston\'s South End/Lower Roxbury community by hiring a group of 14 teens as youth organizers. Through the TE training process, these youth identified their initial goal of finding solutions to the epidemic of gang violence that had taken the lives of several of their friends and was filling their neighborhoods with hatred and fear. The strategy they developed included organizing a series of community meetings for youth, police, and adults. This process culminated in the first Youth Peace Conference in May 1993, which brought together five rival gangs to create a peace treaty.</p>\r\n<p>As an integral part of these community change initiatives, the young people emphasized the connection between gang violence and the lack of jobs and educational opportunities available to urban youth. In addition, they highlighted the pervasive racial and class biases that were helping fuel the rage that many urban youth were expressing through gang-related and other destructive and self-destructive activities. They successfully focused their organizing efforts to push the city, local businesses, and media outlets to expand youth employment programs. Over the next several years, Teen Empowerment youth organizers implemented strategies that encouraged the Boston Police Department to increase community policing programs and decrease the practice of negatively profiling neighborhood youth.</p>\r\n<p>In the spring of 1994, Teen Empowerment received funding from the Riley Foundation to bring the TE Model into the context of a Boston public high school, thus beginning a 13-year presence in the schools. TE\'s first school-based site opened at Madison Park Technical Vocational High School in September. In 1996 and 1997, TE opened sites at two district high schools, first at the English High School, then at Dorchester High (now the Dorchester Education Complex). Schools sites used the TE Model to systematically involve young people in analyzing their school community, determining the priority issues that needed to be addressed, and then developing and carrying out strategies to address the identified issues.</p>\r\n<p>TE\'s community-based work began expanding in 2003 with a site in Rochester, NY. In 2004, TE opened a site in Somerville, MA. In 2006 and 2007, TE opened sites in two neighborhoods of Boston: first in the Bowdoin/Geneva area of Dorchester, then in Egleston Square, Roxbury.</p>\r\n<p>All sites use the TE Model to systematically involve young people in analyzing their school community, determining the priority issues that need to be addressed, and then developing and carrying out strategies to address the identified issues.</p>\r\n<p>Teen Empowerment has organized hundreds of school and community reform initiatives since 1992, and our focus continues to be on youth organizing--developing effective strategies that involve youth in creating positive social and institutional change in their communities and schools. In recent years TE has also expanded its work to include&nbsp;adapting the model\'s component parts&nbsp;as tools to increase productivity in adult work settings and to enhance the effectiveness of other youth and educational service providers. This work includes designing and facilitating training sessions for teachers, police, and human service and youth service providers; developing curricula for schools, residential treatment facilities, and vocational training programs; and developing&nbsp;materials&nbsp;that make Teen Empowerment methods available to all.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zOC1uJMPiME&list=UURdnHCTRCSMqzhMQM1cLAcA&index=1',9,0,0,'','http://www.facebook.com/groups/14694955577/','2013-03-16 16:23:09','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'the-center-for-teen-empowerment',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(109,'Feeding America','35 East Wacker Drive Suite 2000','Chicago ','IL',60601,'www.feedingamerica.org','36-3673599','<p>Feeding America, formerly America\'s Second Harvest, is the nation\'s leading domestic hunger-relief charity. Our mission is to feed America\'s hungry through a nationwide network of member food banks and engage our country in the fight to end hunger. Each year, the Feeding America network provides food assistance to more than 25 million low-income people facing hunger in the United States, including more than nine million children and nearly three million seniors. Our network of more than 200 food banks serves all 50 states, the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico. The Feeding America network secures and distributes more than two billion pounds of donated food and grocery products annually.</p>','<p>MISSION AND VALUES</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Feeding America is the nation\'s leading domestic hunger-relief charity. Our mission is to feed America\'s hungry through a nationwide network of member food banks and engage our country in the fight to end hunger.</p>\r\n<p>Feeding America has adopted the following Statement of Values, which guides all of our actions and planning.</p>\r\n<p>Respect&nbsp;<br />We respect the inherent worth and dignity of every person and treat all with justice, equity and compassion. We honor the lives, concerns and stories of people in need and expect our partners to do the same. We accept one another and encourage diversity of thoughts and ideas.</p>\r\n<p>Stewardship and Accountability&nbsp;<br />We keep faith with the public trust through the efficient and compassionate use of resources entrusted to us and are mindful that our mission is accomplished through the generosity of others. We maintain and communicate accurate and timely information on hunger research, education, advocacy and service. We evaluate and account regularly for how resources are used to implement and achieve our mission.</p>\r\n<p>Collaboration&nbsp;<br />We believe in the power of community. We collaborate and build strong relationships, based on trust, with and among those who share our vision of creating a hunger-free America. We work together to accomplish the vision at the national and local levels, valuing each other&rsquo;s roles and using an open process and honest communication. We seek out and are responsive to the input and counsel of our partners.</p>\r\n<p>Urgency&nbsp;<br />We operate with an acute sense of urgency that reflects the immediate needs of people struggling with hunger. We challenge our employees, volunteers and partners to embrace the same sense of urgency to accomplish our shared vision.</p>\r\n<p>Service&nbsp;<br />We believe service to others is fundamental to creating a hunger-free America. We serve with excellence, compassion and responsiveness to meet the needs of those with whom we work, internally and externally. The better we serve, the more people we bring together in commitment to our vision.</p>\r\n<p>Integrity&nbsp;<br />We act with honesty, trust and openness and deliver on commitments. We act within the spirit of agreements, contracts and the law. Our intentions and actions will be transparent and above reproach.</p>\r\n<p>Diversity&nbsp;<br />We believe that the ethnic, cultural and social diversity of our nation should be reflected in our staff, Board and network.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','http://youtu.be/IYj-09p3CYE',1,0,1,'@FeedingAmerica','https://www.facebook.com/FeedingAmerica','2013-03-22 17:50:43','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'feeding-america',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(111,'ActionAid USA','1420 K Street NW','Washington','DC',20005,'www.actionaidusa.org','52-2277575','<p>ActionAid works on the ground and in the halls of power to end poverty. We work in more than 40 countries across Africa, Asia and Latin America, with over 25 million poor people. Our work seeks to create and sustain better futures by providing relief from disasters and conflicts, empowering women, fighting hunger, holding governments accountable, and making education accessible. We listen to and learn from poor people to identify and help them fulfill their own needs, encouraging them to lobby decision-makers in their own countries, and campaigning and calling for change from those who hold power on the international stage. ActionAid works with coalitions of poor and excluded people from around the world, bringing their perspectives to bear on US policies that affect developing countries. We bring their voices into the American political arena and strengthen domestic support for changes in development policy.</p>','<p>We&rsquo;re ActionAid. We&rsquo;re people who are dedicated to ending the extreme poverty that kills 28 children every minute of every day. We&rsquo;re a non-profit and much more. We&rsquo;re a partnership between people in poor countries and people in rich countries &ndash; all working together to end poverty for good. Vision: A world without poverty in which every person can exercise his or her right to a life of dignity. Mission: To work with poor and marginalized people to eradicate poverty by overcoming the injustice and inequality that cause it.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mlOX8kILcaA&list=UUTE7Owq8v-i_Nzz3-i5773w&index=15',6,0,0,'https://twitter.com/ActionAidUSA','https://www.facebook.com/actionaidusa','2013-04-08 16:34:25','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'actionaid-usa',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(113,'AID FOR AIDS ','515 Greenwich Street, Suite 506','New York','NY',10013,'www.aidforaids.org','13-3954568','<p>AID FOR AIDS International (AFAI) is a non-profit 501 (c) (3) organization committed to improving the quality of life of people living with HIV or AIDS (PLWHAs) in developing countries and who are immigrants to the United States of America. We work to empower PLWHAs, their caregivers, and the community at large by providing access to medications, health education, HIV prevention strategies and advocacy and by promoting leadership and capacity building for individuals and organizations.</p>','','http://youtu.be/u14cfVL4PdM',5,0,0,'@AIDFORAIDSINTL','www.facebook.com/aidforaids','2013-04-09 18:35:13','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'aid-for-aids',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,'A Place Called Home','2830 South Central Avenue','Los Angeles','CA',90011,'apch.org','95-4427291','<p>A Place Called home is a safe haven in South Central Los Angeles where underserved youth are empowered to take ownership of the quality and direction of their lives through programs in education, arts, and well-being; and are inspired to make a meaningful difference in their community and the world.</p>','<p>If you grow up in the wrong zip code, the math is stacked against you&mdash;in fact, that is the single strongest predictor of your destiny.<br /><br /> In the Los Angeles 90011 zip code, poverty, malnutrition and mediocre education are the starting points for thousands of children every year.<br /><br /> The odds are tragically high that they will grow up to enter a cycle of early parenthood, depression, drug abuse, violence, crime, jail time&hellip; and that the cycle will repeat with their children. When those same young people have support to develop their best potential, they become carpenters, nurses, social workers, teachers, doctors, inventors, artists and leaders.<br /><br /> They make positive choices, create their own destinies and influence their siblings, their children, their communities and the world.At APCH we provide FREE programs and services every day in education, literacy, counseling, nutrition, dance, music, recording, art, electronic media, athletics, gardening, high school dropout recovery, college preparation, college applications and scholarships, and vocational preparation and intenships. We also distribute food, clothing, books and household essentials to thousands year round. In 2012 we supported 68 first-generation scholars to go to college. Through love, nourishment, education, guidance and training,A Place Called Home is a predictor of destiny for hundreds of children, age 8-21, who cross our threshold every day&mdash;more than 17,000 over the past 20 years.</p>','http://youtu.be/9zPON-OYGZI',9,1,1,'https://twitter.com/apch2830','https://www.facebook.com/APCH2830?ref=hl','2013-04-09 19:07:24','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'a-place-called-home',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,'Action on Smoking and Health','701 - 4th St, NW','Washington','DC',20001,'www.ash.org','13-2603590','<p>We seek to combat tobacco related deaths on all fronts because we find it unacceptable that 1 person dies every 6 seconds from a tobacco related illness.</p>','<p>Founded in 1967, ASH is one of the oldest tobacco control organizations in the US. Throughout our 4 decades of leadership in the anti-tobacco movement, ASH has helped transform the perception of tobacco by the American public from casual acceptane as a normal behavior to an unacceptable health risk.<br /><br /> ASH develops new and effective ways to leverage our experience, expertise, and leadership in the tobacco-free movement to counter the power and influence of the global tobacco industry.<br /><br /> We organize and direct the work of the Framework Convention Alliance (FCA), a coalition of over 350 organizations from more than 100 countries. The FCA works to sustain effective tobacco control in vulnerable countries and to limit the influence of the tobacco industry.<br /><br /> ASH and FCA were key players in the adoption and ongoing ratification and implementation of the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC), the world\'s 1st global public health treaty!<br /><br /> The tobacco epidemic is global and so must be the solutions. From advocating for bans on cigarette advertising and smoking in public places to challenging the influence of the multinational tobacco industry - ASH takes action on a global scale to save lives!<br /><br /></p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RnRReNo-By4',5,0,0,'@AshOrg','www.facebook.com/ASHglobalAction','2013-04-09 22:06:06','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'action-on-smoking-and-health',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,'American Institute for Cancer Research','1759 R Street, NW,','Washington','DC',20009,'http://www.aicr.org/','52-1238026','<p>The American Institute for Cancer Research is one of the nation&rsquo;s largest cancer organizations, focusing on the relation of diet, physical activity and weight management to cancer. AICR supports innovative research in cancer prevention, treatment and survivorship at universities, hospitals and research centers worldwide. It has committed its resources to interpreting this research for application by the public. AICR provides a wide range of education programs that help millions of Americans learn to make changes for lower cancer risk.</p>','<p>In 1982, American Institute for Cancer Research (AICR) was founded to advance the simple but then-radical idea that cancer could be prevented.</p>\r\n<p>AICR focused on the link between diet and cancer, and immediately began supporting cutting-edge research in this area and educating the public about the results.</p>\r\n<p>Today, we continue to fund research in the field of nutrition, physical activity and cancer prevention, treatment and survival.</p>\r\n<p>We interpret the results of that research, along with findings from the global scientific community, to craft reliable, evidence-based recommendations for lower cancer risk.</p>\r\n<p>Our Impact</p>\r\n<p>AICR has changed the modern understanding of cancer.</p>\r\n<p>Only decades ago, most believed that cancer simply strikes the unlucky &ndash; and that nothing can be done about it.</p>\r\n<p>Today, thanks to millions of dollars of AICR research, the world knows better.</p>\r\n<p>Our research sheds unique light on the cancer process &ndash; and pinpoints the specific lifestyle choices that will save hundreds of thousands of lives every year in the US alone.</p>\r\n<p>Our research also offers hope that cancer patients and survivors can take control of their health during and after treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Thirty years ago, AICR stepped in to fill a critical research gap.</p>\r\n<p>Today, thousands of studies later, we have produced the hard evidence that turned a once-radical notion into a universally accepted medical fact:</p>\r\n<p>Every one of us can take steps to prevent cancer.</p>','',5,0,1,'','','2013-04-18 00:18:43','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'american-institute-for-cancer-research',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(119,'Boys & Girls Clubs of Santa Monica','1220 Lincoln Blvd.','Santa Monica','CA',90401,'www.smbgc.org','951890706','<p>Our mission is to inspire and enable all young people, especially those who need us most, to realize their full potential as caring, responsible and productive citizens.</p>','<p>The Boys &amp; Girls Clubs of Santa Monica is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization dedicated to providing youth a safe and productive place to go when they need it most: after school and on non-school days.</p>','http://youtu.be/n9us9IRSRsM',9,0,0,'smbgc','https://www.facebook.com/smbgcfan','2013-04-24 23:05:17','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'boys-girls-clubs-of-santa-monica',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(120,'Tee It Up Foundation, Inc. - \"Tee It Up Fore Kids\"','5665 Atlanta Highway, Suite 103','Alpharetta','Georgia',30004,'www.teeitupforekids.org','26-0397241','<p>Changing the lives of children \"One Child at a Time\"</p>','<p>Tee It Up Foundation is a 501c3 charitable foundation comprised solely of volunteers dedicated to supporting children with special need and changing lives \"One Child at a Time\"</p>','',5,0,0,'','','2013-04-25 16:57:18','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'tee-it-up-foundation-inc-tee-it-up-fore-kids',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(121,'Anxiety and Depression Association of America','8701 Georgia Ave., Suite 412','Silver Spring','MD',20910,'www.adaa.org','52-124-8820','<p>The Anxiety and Depression Association of America (ADAA) is the leader in education, training, and research for anxiety, depression, PTSD, and stress-related disorders.</p>','<p>Anxiety disorders are the most common psychiatric illnesses affecting children and adults. An estimated 40 million American adults suffer from anxiety disorders. Only about one-third of those suffering from an anxiety disorder receive treatment, even though the disorders are highly treatable.<br /><br /> ADAA leads the way, improving the lives of millions of children and adults:<br /><br /> Promotes professional and public awareness of anxiety, depression, and related disorders and their impact on people\'s lives.<br /><br /> Encourages the advancement of scientific knowledge about causes and treatment of anxiety, depression, and related disorders.<br /><br /> Links people who need treatment with the health care professionals who provide it.<br /><br /> Helps people find appropriate treatment and develop self-help skills.<br /><br /> Works to reduce the stigma surrounding anxiety, depression, and related disorders.<br /><br /></p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=gkSypHQ-a9g',5,0,0,'https://twitter.com/Got_Anxiety','https://www.facebook.com/AnxietyAndDepressionAssociationOfAmerica?notif_t=page_new_likes','2013-04-25 20:50:40','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'anxiety-and-depression-association-of-america',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(122,'Camp Summit, Inc.','17210 Campbell Road, Suite 180-W','Dallas','TX',75252,'www.campsummittx.org','752488486','<p>The mission of Camp Summit is to providebarrier-free outdoor experiences that promote personal growth and foster independence for children and adults with disabilities.</p>','<p>Camp Summit offers weeklong camp sessions for children and adults with disabilities during spring break, the summer months, and during the fall. Additionally, weekend sessions and respite days are offered in the spring and fall. Campers are offered a wide variety of traditional camp activities in our barrier-free environment including a specially-designed swimming pool, adapted tree house, horseback riding ramps, adapted ropes challenge course, covered outdoor gymnasium, lodge with fireplace, fishing pond, camp sites and the outdoor chapel.<br /> There are no other camps in our region and only a handful of camps in the United States that offer a camping program comparable to Camp Summit. We are unique because:<br /><br /> - Our goal is to accept campers without regard to the severity of their disability;<br /> - We have no upper age limit for adult campers;<br /> - Campers apply to and are accepted directly by our organization without an intermediary agency;<br /> - We offer a 2:1 ratio of campers to counselors, with special 1:1 assistance when needed;<br /> - We provide on-site medical personnel, including Registered Nurses and a Physician on-call to ensure the safety and well being of our campers; and<br /> - Financial assistance programs are available to low-income families including a sliding scale fee structure and camp scholarship program.</p>','',8,0,0,'','https://www.facebook.com/CampSummitTX','2013-04-25 21:46:59','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'camp-summit-inc',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(123,'Bean\'s Cafe','1101 E 3rd Ave','Anchorage','Alaska',99501,'www.beanscafe.org','92-0072522','<p>&ldquo;Feed the hungry and shelter the homeless without discrimination during the day.&rdquo;</p>','<p>Bean&rsquo;s Caf&eacute; was incorporated February 20, 1979 as a privately supported, grass root, non-sectarian, stand-alone organization with no national affiliation. Bean&rsquo;s Caf&eacute; basic mission is to feed and provide day shelter for Anchorage&rsquo;s poor and hungry, 365 days a year.<br /><br /> Today direct services now encompass basic first aid, mail service, social service advocacy and assistance for those seeking employment, transportation, housing, medical, legal, alcohol or drug rehabilitation and education. Further we work collaboratively with a variety of community agencies in emergency and long term assistance in mental health, veteran&rsquo;s assistance, disability, financial and case management. Bean&rsquo;s Caf&eacute; also serves as a day shelter and night shelter which provides a safe alternative to life on the streets. All of our services are free of charge to everyone.</p>','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXGDGcZAiWE',8,0,0,'beanscafeak','https://www.facebook.com/beanscafe?ref=hl','2013-04-25 22:55:38','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'bean-s-cafe',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(125,'Chesapeake Bay Foundation','6 Herndon Avenue','Annapolis','MD',21403,'www.cbf.org','52-6065757','<p>Save the Bay, and keep it saved, as defined by reaching a 70 on CBF\'s Health Index.</p>','<p>Our Vision<br /><br /> The Chesapeake Bay and its tributary rivers, broadly recognized as a national treasure, will be highly productive and in good health as measured by established water quality standards. The result will be clear water, free of impacts from toxic contaminants, and with healthy oxygen levels. Natural filters on both the land and in the water will provide resilience to the entire Chesapeake Bay system and serve as valuable habitat for both terrestrial and aquatic life.</p>','https://www.youtube.com/chesapeakebayfound',4,0,0,'https://twitter.com/chesapeakebay','https://www.facebook.com/chesapeakebay','2013-04-30 12:51:08','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'chesapeake-bay-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(126,'charity: water','200 Varick Street, Suite 201 ','New York','NY',10014,'http://www.charitywater.org/','22-3936753','<p>charity: water is a non-profit organization bringing clean, safe drinking water to people in developing countries. We use 100% of public donations to directly fund sustainable water solutions in areas of greatest need.</p>','<p>charity: water is a non-profit organization bringing clean, safe drinking water to people in developing countries. We use 100% of public donations to directly fund sustainable water solutions in areas of greatest need.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BCHhwxvQqxg',6,1,1,'https://twitter.com/charitywater','https://www.facebook.com/charitywater','2013-04-30 14:51:05','2013-09-04 18:56:05',1,'charity-water',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(127,'Capital Area Food Bank of DC','4900 Puerto Rico Ave. NE','Washington','DC',20017,'www.capitalareafoodbank.org','52-1167581','<p>The mission of the Capital Area Food Bank is to feed those who suffer from hunger in the Washington, The mission of the Capital Area Food Bank is to feed those who suffer from hunger in the Washington metro area by acquiring food and distributing it through its network of partner agencies; and educating, empowering and enlightening the community about the issues of hunger and nutrition. CAFB is a member of Feeding America, a national network of 200 food banks.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Vision</strong>: We envision a community in which everyone has access to sufficient nutritious food.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Mission</strong>: The mission of the Capital Area Food Bank is to feed those who suffer from hunger in the Washington, D.C. Metropolitan Area by acquiring food and distributing it through our network of member agencies; and to educate, empower and enlighten the community about the issues of hunger and nutrition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Values</strong>: We believe that access to nutritious food is a basic human right. We are committed to responding to the needs of our community through food distribution and support services.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The Capital Area Food Bank</strong>:</p>\r\n<div id=\"list_condense\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Distributes 33 million pounds of food annually, half of which is fresh produce</li>\r\n<li>Serves 478,100 people in the region struggling with hunger</li>\r\n<li>Delivers 120 fresh produce drops each month to 90 sites throughout the Washington metro area</li>\r\n<li>Spends 92 cents of each dollar raised for food distribution, transportation and programs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>','http://youtu.be/KCkMELhYn2w',8,0,0,'@foodbankmetrodc','https://www.facebook.com/CapitalAreaFoodBank','2013-04-30 17:38:40','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'capital-area-food-bank-of-dc',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(129,'Friends Without A Border','1123 Broadway','New York','NY',10010,'www.fwab.org','13-3880402','<p>Friends Without A Border is committed to care for, educate, and provide for destitute, abandoned, neglected, ill and dependent children and their families of certain foreign countries. We started in Cambodia and will maintain our presence there indefinitely. Beginning in 2013, Friends will replicate its work in Luang Prabang, Laos and start construction on a freestanding pediatric building at the site of the Luang Prabang Provincial Hospital.</p>','<p>Founded in 1996 by world-renowned photographer Kenro Izu, Friends Without A Border (Friends) is an international nongovernmental organization (NGO) that is committed to providing high-quality and compassionate healthcare to children in Southeast Asia.<br /><br /> In 1999, Friends opened Angkor Hospital for Children (AHC) in Siem Reap, Cambodia. AHC takes a 360 approach to pediatric health care using the successful model of: <br /> treatment + education + prevention.<br /><br /> Earlier this year, Friends and AHC accomplished the long-held goal of a self-sufficient hospital as Friends handed over the management and operations to the dedicated and passionate staff of AHC. Friends will continue to be a presence at AHC and help with their fundraising efforts.<br /><br /> In January 2013, working in partnership with the Luang Prabang Provincial Hospital and Health Department, Friends embarked on a new endeavor to deliver high-quality pediatric care to the children of Laos. Later this year, Friends will begin construction on Lao Friends Hospital for Children.<br /><br /> Our Goals:<br /><br /> - Provide high-quality medical care for children in a warm, supportive environment.<br /> - Support and provide continuing education of healthcare professionals throughout Cambodia and in other countries so that they will become the clinicians and educators of the future.<br /> - Improve the health, nutrition, and hygiene of local communities through outreach programs and homecare.<br /> - Stimulate research to develop sound healthcare practices appropriate for local conditions.</p>','',5,0,0,'twitter.com/fwabny','www.facebook.com/fwabny','2013-04-30 20:35:33','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'friends-without-a-border',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(130,'Global Action','7660 Goddard St., Ste. 200','Colorado Springs','CO',80920,'www.globalaction.com','84-1471157','<p>Engaging the Global Church for Action</p>','<p>Global Action is a Christian not-for-profit based in Colorado Springs, CO. In existence since 1998, Global Action engages the Global Church for Action by providing leadership training and tools for local churches to bring the Gospel of Jesus Christ to people who need hope, education, training, and community transformation.</p>','',6,0,0,'global_action','https://www.facebook.com/globalaction','2013-04-30 20:45:53','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'global-action',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(131,'Food for Others','2938 Prosperity Avenue','Fairfax','VA',22031,'www.foodforothers.org','54-177757','<p>Our Mission is to obtain and distribute free food to the hungry of Northern Virginia and to support food programs of other community-based organizations. We provide a channel for people to volunteer their services to help their neighbors in need.</p>','<p>In our nation\'s capital area, many families are struggling to provide for basic needs like food and shelter. Unfortunately, many times, some cannot even afford that. Since 1995, Food for Others has been helping many of these families.<br /><br /> Food for Others is Northern Virginia&rsquo;s primary safety net for those needing food when an emergency strikes, and for the growing number of working poor who are unable to make ends meet and need to supplement their inadequate food supplies.<br /><br /> Food for Others obtains much of its food through food rescue operations and food drives. Staff and volunteers pick up good food that would be thrown away from local grocery stores and other retail food establishments. The food is brought to the warehouse for temporary storage, including refrigeration as appropriate. Food drives provide most of our non-perishable food.<br /><br /> Our Mission is to obtain and distribute free food to the hungry of Northern Virginia and to support food programs of other community-based organizations. We provide a channel for people to volunteer their services to help their neighbors in need.<br /><br /> Local merchants, the USDA, food drives, and crop harvests provide the food; volunteers and staff provide the hands; and charitable contributions and fundraising events provide the funds. Charitable contributions provide a major part of Food for Others\' budget. About 96 cents out of every revenue dollar is used for program expenses.</p>','',8,1,0,'www.twitter.com/foodforothers','http://www.facebook.com/pages/Food-for-Others/64550384513','2013-04-30 20:56:03','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'food-for-others',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(132,'Defeat Diabetes Foundation, Inc','150 153rd Ave Suite 300','Madeira Beach','FL',33708,'http://www.defeatdiabetes.org/','EIN: 59-3027985','<p>The Mission of Defeat Diabetes Foundation is the prevention, early identification and self-management of the global epidemic, diabetes. We work with individuals and organizations worldwide through our awareness, interactive and assistance programs.</p>','<p>Defeat Diabetes Foundation, Inc. (DDF), is a 501(c)3 charity, established in September 1990, was incorporated on November 21, 1991 under the laws of the state of Florida as a nonprofit corporation, and is currently nationally recognized.<br /><br /> Vision<br /><br /> The vision for the organization is to show through the actions of the Executive Director, Andrew P. Mandell - Mr. Diabetes&reg; (and other diabetic staff members), that diabetics are neither helpless nor hopeless and can lead productive lives. DDF will provide accurate, reliable, up-to-date information about the self-management of diabetes and show how Mr. Diabetes&reg; utilizes these techniques in his daily life to avoid the significant complications of the disease. He will put a name and face on the disease and show through his actions how to advocate for appropriate solutions to diabetic issues.<br /><br /> Programs and Services<br /><br /> DDF conducts nationwide programs that focus on awareness, prevention and early detection of diabetes.<br /><br /> The Foundation maintains a website as a source of information for anyone interested in health and especially for \"pre-diabetics\" and diabetics that features content about diabetes, its complications and the importance of self-management. Defeat Diabetes Foundation conducts programs each year to promote awareness, prevention and early detection. <br /><br /> The Defeat Diabetes Foundation Website,www.DefeatDiabetes.org: A source for everyone interested in health, especially Diabetics and Pre-Diabetics. It features a free on-line E-Lerts&trade; newsletter and very comprehensive and understandable information about Diabetes health, research, nutrition and fitness. There is original content from medical and professional personnel in their areas of expertise. It also contains sections on resources for diabetic support groups, diabetic children\'s camps, latest news and much, much more. <br /><br /> KIDD&trade; and Schools Programs: Currently targets elementary, middle schools and civic organizations throughout the country by distributing Free of Charge the Foundations unique Defeat Diabetes&reg; Screening Test brochure. We believe that the earlier diabetes is addressed the better chance to control it or even prevent it. <br /><br /> KIDD&trade; Curriculum: is a health related program designed for schools, youth and community organizations to educate children and their community about diabetes. <br /> Pet Diabetes Awareness and Prevention Program (PetDAP): Almost all veterinarians admit diabetes is under-reported and could affect as many as one in 50 of our pets. The Mission of Defeat Diabetes Foundation\'s Pet Diabetes Awareness and Prevention Program is the prevention, early identification and management of pet diabetes.<br /> Medical Supplies: This program distributes donated medical supplies to individuals and organizations worldwide.<br /> D.A.N. Project (Diabetes Awareness Now): This Defeat Diabetes&reg; Awareness Project is a Public Service Announcement campaign about the dangers of undiagnosed diabetes. Public Service Announcements about diabetes awareness and prevention have aired on television and radio in targeted local markets and nationally. Established in memory of Dan Kerner.<br /> Defeat Diabetes Foundation mails information to the general public including the Defeat Diabetes&reg; Screening Test Brochures.<br /> The Media Outreach Campaigns informs and educates The Media of the dangers of diabetes. <br /> Advocacy Program: Mr. Diabetes&reg; testifies before Governors, Senators, Congressmen, State Legislatures, Mayors, City Councils, and Civic Organizations to bring awareness of the diabetic condition to governments and their health agencies. The Foundation also provides information to the public regarding legislation pending that would impact diabetes related programs and services. <br /> Mr. Diabetes&reg; meets with leaders of the medical community as well as hospitals, Diabetes Support Groups and Senior Citizen Groups, Schools, Camps, and other venues.<br /> We are committed to continuing this work for the 26 million diabetics and 79 million pre-diabetics in the United States with the disease. Diabetes is a global epidemic and we are working with individuals and organizations worldwide to promote awareness, early detection and self-management of the disease.<br /> The Foundation is supported through donations by concerned individuals and is operated by contracted, salaried and volunteer services.<br /> Defeat Diabetes Foundation does NOT provide professional medical advice. The information we provide is intended to help you better understand diabetes. It is NOT intended to replace the advice of your physician.</p>','',5,0,0,'@DefeatDiabetes1','https://www.facebook.com/pages/Defeat-Diabetes-Foundation/132906600065886?ref=ts','2013-05-01 20:59:01','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'defeat-diabetes-foundation-inc',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(133,'Breastcancer.org','7 Lancaster Avenue, 3rd Floor','Ardmore','PA',19003,' http://www.breastcancer.org','23-3082851','<p>Breastcancer.org is a nonprofit organization dedicated to providing the most reliable, complete, and up-to-date information about breast health and breast cancer. Our mission is to help women and their loved ones make sense of the complex medical and personal information about breast cancer, so they can make the best decisions for their lives.</p>','<p>In the crowded and confusing world of online medical information, Breastcancer.org stands out as the place where anyone affected by breast cancer can find what they need. With over 6,000 pages of expert-reviewed, up-to-date medical information, the site walks users through each phase of the disease &mdash; from diagnosis, treatment, and side effects, to managing the everyday realities of breast cancer. The site also offers an extensive section on prevention, with advice on environmental and lifestyle choices that can reduce the risk of developing breast cancer or its recurrence. In addition to providing invaluable information, Breastcancer.org hosts a close-knit online community where those affected by breast cancer share their experiences, knowledge, and support. Breastcancer.org&rsquo;s expertise and community are also optimized for access by mobile devices.</p>','http://youtu.be/7zc1deTB8zE',5,0,1,'https://twitter.com/Breastcancerorg','https://www.facebook.com/breastcancerorg','2013-05-01 21:48:40','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'breastcancer-org',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(134,'Food Bank of the Rockies','10700 E. 45th AVE','Denver','CO',80239,'www.foodbankrockies.org','84-0772672','<p>We will end hunger by efficiently procuring and distributing food and essentials to the hungry, through our programs and partner agencies.</p>','<p>At Food Bank of the Rockies, we provide food for more than 350,000 people annually. We do this by distributing 88,000 meals each day through over 1,000 hunger relief partner agencies and our direct service programs.<br /><br /> Our food bank is one of the largest hunger relief organizations in the Rocky Mountain Region. Thanks to your donations, 96 cents of every dollar we receive goes directly to our food distribution programs.<br /><br /> You can help fight hunger in our community by making a contribution of your time and resources. Every dollar donated to Food Bank of the Rockies provides four meals to our neighbors in need!<br /><br /></p>','http://www.youtube.com/foodbankrockies',5,0,0,'@foodbankrockies','https://www.facebook.com/FoodBankRockies','2013-05-02 15:13:37','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'food-bank-of-the-rockies',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(135,'Earth Force Inc','2555 W 34th Ave','Denver','Colorado',80211,'www.earthforce.org','58-1806705','<p>Earth Force engages young people as active citizens who improve the environment and their communities now and in the future.</p>','<p>Earth Force engages young people as active citizens who improve the environment and their communities now and in the future. At Earth Force, we are passionate about young people finding their voice and assuming leadership roles in solving environmental problems. Through our four Centers of Excellence, Earth Force inspires communities to change how they engage with young people. By connecting community partners and institutions to relevant learning and action, young people become agents of change, addressing issues in their schools and their community.</p>','',3,NULL,NULL,'@earthforce','www.facebook.com/EarthForceGREEN','2013-05-06 16:37:55','2013-07-05 13:51:07',NULL,'earth-force-inc',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(137,'Humane Society of South Mississippi','2615 25th Ave','Gulfport','Mississippi',39501,'www.hssm.org','64-6034439','<p>The mission of the Humane Society of South Mississippi is to save and enhance the lives of pets through cooperative and innovative approaches to adoption, spay/neuter, sheltering and community engagement.</p>','<p>We Are Committed to Ending Pet Overpopulation &amp; Homelessness.<br /><br /> The Humane Society of South Mississippi (HSSM) is home to 300 homeless pets on any given day. Our dream is to make South Mississippi a community in which no adoptable pet is ever euthanized and we are working to Countdown to Zero by 2015! <br /><br /> We Are A 100% Independent Nonprofit Organization.<br /><br /> The Humane Society of South Mississippi (HSSM) receives no &ldquo;trickle down&rdquo; funding from any national animal welfare organization or any local, state, or federal governmental funding in support of our operations. HSSM depends on the generosity of our community to provide the high quality services and compassion we are renowned for Please consider making a lifesaving donation today!<br /><br /> We Are NOT Your Average &ldquo;Pound.&rdquo;<br /><br /> The Humane Society of South Mississippi (HSSM) strives to provide a friendly, clean and fun environment for the people and pets that we serve. Our 40,000 square foot facility is modeled after leading children&rsquo;s museums and is more like a trip to a funhouse than a trip to an animal shelter Don&rsquo;t believe us? Check out this video below.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hx1kqbwQjxU',1,0,0,'hssm','facebook.com/MyHSSM','2013-05-07 16:54:53','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'humane-society-of-south-mississippi',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(140,'Helen Woodward Animal Center','P.O. Box 64','Rancho Santa Fe','CA',92067,'www.animalcenter.org','23-7228287','<p>Helen Woodward Animal Center\'s passionate belief that animals help people and people help animals through trust, unconditional love, and respect, creates a legacy of caring. Sharing this philosophy with others, the Center inspires and teaches, locally and globally, the importance of the animal-human bond.</p>','<p>The Center offers many animal-centered programs and services to benefit both humans and pets in our community:<br /><br /> - Therapeutic Riding: Weekly lessons with our specially trained horses provide children and adults with physical and mental challenges with a unique therapy that improves balance and muscle development, mobility, concentration, short term memory, and motor skills, among others. AniMeals: In partnership with meal delivery programs such as Meals-On-Wheels, the program provided pet food delivery at no charge to elderly and homebound individuals who otherwise might be at risk of losing their companion animal because they either cannot afford pet food and/or are unable to leave the house to purchase it. <br /><br /> - Pet Encounter Therapy (PET): Program volunteers bring the tactile benefits and unconditional love that only an animal can provide to individuals in senior homes, centers for abused children, hospitals, and other institutional settings. Interaction with animals is proven to provide both physical and emotional benefits and we see evidence of this during our visits each day.<br /><br /> - Education: Critter Camp and other education programs teach children ages 4 and above the importance of treating all living beings humanely and with respect. In 2011 we held Summer, Winter, and President&rsquo;s Week camps as well as tours and other activities throughout the year.<br /><br /> - Adoptions: The adoptions program takes in and finds homes for orphaned dogs and cats, in 2011 2,498 cats and dogs were placed in forever homes.<br /><br /> - Club Pet: A top-rated boarding facility that provides quality care for cats, dogs, birds, and exotics while their owners are away throughout the year.<br /><br /> - Equine Hospital: Serves the local equine community from race horses to family pets with state-of-the-art equipment and was staffed 24 hours/day, 7 days /week in 2011.<br /><br /> - Companion Animal Hospital: Provides veterinary care for all types of small companion animals, from cats and dogs to reptiles and birds, seven days a week.<br /><br /> - ACES: Animal Center Education Services provided workshops free of charge to animal welfare personnel from across the country with best practices on how to run their organizations as a business to save more lives.<br /><br /> Accomplishments<br /><br /> Today, our Adoptions program saves the lives of nearly 3,000 pets each year, and our other programs impact approximately 7,000 additional animals that we see through our hospitals, boarding facility, and AniMeals programs. Our Pet Encounter Therapy program has grown to reach nearly 20,000 children and adults each year, while Therapeutic Riding serves 55 clients each week and AniMeals serves nearly 200 human clients. Our Education program now sees approximately 15,000 children each year through our Critter Camp programs as well as special tours and visits for groups.</p>','',8,0,0,'@HWAC','www.facebook.com/helenwoodwardanimalcenter','2013-05-08 16:58:52','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'helen-woodward-animal-center',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(141,'Love146','PO Box 8266','New Haven','CT',6530,'','20-1168284','<p>Love146 works towards the end of child trafficking and exploitation by caring for survivors, preventing it from happening, and empowering a growing abolition movement.</p>','<p>Love146 is an international human rights organization working to end child trafficking and exploitation by caring for survivors, providing prevention education to children, training professionals working with exploited youth and empowering an international movement of abolition. Since 2002, Love146 has worked towards a sustainable, long-term and holistic approach to the problem of child trafficking and exploitation, caring for children throughout Asia, Europe and the United States. We\'re committed to abolition. Nothing less.</p>','http://youtu.be/gYgkiaLwgyU',9,0,0,'www.twitter.com/love146','www.facebook.com/love146.org','2013-05-08 17:54:43','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'love146',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(143,'International Institute of Rural Reconstruction','40 Exchange Place, Suite 1205','New York','New York',10005,'iirr.org','13-617-5722','<p>Through its work in Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, South Sudan, Zimbabwe, Cambodia, and The Philippines, IIRR has been working in true partnership with rural communities to empower them to lead and manage their own development since 1960. IIRR is actively engaging communities to educate children, adapt farming practices to a changing climate, bring nutritious foods to the table and the market, plan for and mitigate disasters, gain business skills and build assets.</p>','<p>The International Institute of Rural Reconstruction (IIRR) grew out of the poverty-fighting work of Dr. Y.C. James Yen, who grew up in China, attended Yale University, and then returned to China to start the Mass Education Movement. He later created IIRR as an educational institute to inspire and lead rural reconstruction efforts worldwide. <br /><br /> Since 1960, IIRR has been doing just that, with offices in Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, South Sudan, Zimbabwe, Cambodia, and The Philippines. Dr. Yen&rsquo;s philosophy remains with IIRR in its Credo of Rural Reconstruction: Go to the People, Live among them, Learn from them, Plan with them, Work with them, Start with what they know, Build on what they have, Teach by showing, Learn by doing, Not a showcase, but a pattern, Not odds-and-ends, but a system, Not piecemeal, but an integrated approach, Not to conform, but to transform, Not relief but release.<br /><br /> For its unique and effective model of community-led development, IIRR has been awarded the Ramon Magsaysay Award for International Understanding and the Alan Shawn Feinstein Hunger Award.</p>','http://youtu.be/QOJ3i8iM_yQ',6,0,0,'https://twitter.com/IIRR','https://www.facebook.com/IIRR.org','2013-05-09 16:07:31','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'international-institute-of-rural-reconstruction',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(144,'Mentors International','65 Wadsworth Park Drive','Draper','UT',84020,'www.mentorsinternational.org','43-153-6498','<p><strong>Our mission is to end poverty through self reliance.</strong> The mission of Mentors International in developing countries is to assist individuals and families that struggle for self-sufficiency as they attain a self-reliant livelihood. This is achieved by providing enterprise activities and educational assistance such as trainings, character development guidance, counseling, mentoring, and of course, small business loans.</p>','<p>In developing countries, Mentors&rsquo; mission is to provide those with the means and desire to assist the poor in a meaningful and lasting way, with proven and practical methods to extend a hand up, not a handout.<br /><br /> Our values support our mission. Mentors\' operating philosophy and policies are based on the value system that a successful life, business or society can be built only by building individual character.<br /><br /> We generate more impact with a dollar. Your dollar gives over and over again with our perpetual model. Clients repay their loans with interest at reasonable interest rates to Mentors to help fund new loans, making your contribution last.<br /><br /> We don&rsquo;t believe in handouts. With Mentors&rsquo; guiding principle of a hand up, not a handout, the donor-recipient relationship is transformed. Mentors serves only individuals and families that demonstrate integrity and the motivation to lift themselves out of poverty. <br /><br /> We teach accountability. Mentors requires full, on-time repayment of loans. Promoting integrity, Mentors provides follow-up to ensure that its clients implement steps toward accountability in their lives. Mentors&rsquo; loan repayment rate averages at 97 percent. Mentors serves many communities where 100 percent of clients pay back every loan.<br /><br /> We assign our clients a mentor. Unlike many microfinance organizations, Mentors provides a high degree of ongoing, personalized training and mentoring. The knowledge and encouragement clients receive are vital to their success as they build businesses and become self-reliant. <br /><br /> We don&rsquo;t solicit or accept government assistance. All contributions to Mentors are purely voluntary. Mentors does seek grants from family foundations and charitable organizations.</p>','http://youtu.be/IGhpvNahzgg',8,1,1,'@mentors','https://www.facebook.com/MentorsIntl?ref=hl','2013-05-09 16:16:18','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'mentors-international',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(145,'National Coalition Against Domestic Violence','One Broadway, Suite 210 B','Denver','CO',80203,'www.ncadv.org','91-1081344','<p>The Mission of the National Coalition Against Domestic Violence (NCADV) is to organize for collective power by advancing transformative work, thinking and leadership of communities and individuals working to end the violence in our lives.</p>','<h2>NCADV Works To:</h2>\r\n<p>Eliminate Domestic Violence: NCADV is devoted to the elimination of domestic violence in urban and rural areas, across all racial, religious and economic groups. NCADV identifies and works to eradicate the social conditions that perpetuate or condone domestic violence such as sexism, ageism, heterosexism, and able-bodyism and easy access to guns. <br /><br /> Empower Battered Women and Children: NCADV protects and empowers battered women and children through vigilance and sponsorship of national public policy initiatives and federal legislation such as the Violence Against Women Act. <br /><br /> Promote and Unify Direct Service Programs: NCADV serves as the membership organization, the coalition builder and the technical advisor for agencies and programs nationwide that provide domestic violence services. NCADV represents these grassroots organizations with a unified, loud voice. <br /><br /> Alert and Educate the Public: NCADV alerts the public to the facts of domestic violence and educates the public on how to recognize domestic violence and what to do about it; on teen dating violence; on the impact of family violence on children; and on domestic violence against the disabled and the elderly and other marginalized populations. <br /><br /> Promote Partnerships: NCADV partners with corporations and foundations to design and fund innovative programs to eliminate domestic violence and to foster development of safe alternatives within local communities.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/user/TheNCADV',1,0,0,'www.twitter.com/NCADV','www.facebook.com/NCADVMainoffice','2013-05-14 23:31:30','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'national-coalition-against-domestic-violence',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(146,'Next Door Solutions to Domestic Violence','234 East Gish Rd., Suite #200','San Jose','CA',95112,'www.nextdoor.org','94-2420708','<p>Next Door seeks &ldquo;to end domestic violence in the moment and for all time.&rdquo;</p>','<p>Next Door promotes safety for battered women and their children through emergency shelter; multiple points of entry for victims; individuals, system and institutional advocacy; crisis intervention; education for victims and the community; and the changing of community norms through prevention activities.</p>','',1,0,0,'https://twitter.com/NDSolutions','https://www.facebook.com/#!/NextDoorSolutions?fref=ts','2013-05-15 01:47:34','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'next-door-solutions-to-domestic-violence',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(147,'Plant With Purpose','4903 Morena Blvd., Ste 1215','San Diego','CA',92117,'http://www.plantwithpurpose.org/','33-0052976','<p>Plant With Purpose, a Christian non-profit organization, reverses deforestation and poverty around the world by transforming the lives of the rural poor.</p>','<p>Plant With Purpose is a Christian, environmental non-profit organization that transforms lives in rural areas worldwide where poverty is caused by deforestation. Focusing on holistic solutions to poverty, Plant With Purpose has been restoring the lives of the rural poor for over 25 years by planting trees, creating economic opportunity through micro-credit and micro-enterprise, implementing sustainable agriculture programs, and encouraging spiritual renewal.<br /><br /> Our three-part environmental, economic, and spiritual approach to sustainable development transforms the communities and people we work with in the following ways.<br /> 1. Improved Quality of Life <br /> As a result of our work, children and adults enjoy improved health, children attain higher levels of education and women experience greater equality and economic security.<br /><br /> 2. Restored Relationships<br /> Plant With Purpose initiatives help strengthen family relationships, the relationship between people and their environment, and the relationship between people and God.<br /><br /> 3. Self Sufficiency<br /> Our synergistic model of environmental and economic development teaches people to farm in ways that also protect the land, ensuring their long-term prosperity. As a result, these communities continue to thrive long after our work there ends. Our Vision: Plant With Purpose is breaking the vicious cycle of poverty and deforestation by transforming it into a victorious cycle of environmental restoration, economic empowerment, and spiritual renewal. <br /><br /></p>','http://www.youtube.com/plantwithpurpose',6,0,0,'https://twitter.com/plantwpurpose','https://www.facebook.com/PlantWithPurpose','2013-05-15 16:38:22','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'plant-with-purpose',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(148,'PeacePlayers International','901 New York Avenue NW Suite 550 East','Washington','DC',20001,'peaceplayersintl.org','52-2272092 ','<p>PeacePlayers International (PPI) was founded in 2001 on the premise that &ldquo;children who play together can learn to live together.&rdquo; In its nearly eleven years of operations, PPI has reached more than 55,000 participants. Through a groundbreaking peacebuilding-and-leadership development curriculum, PeacePlayers International uses basketball to bring children together and teach them proven tactics for improving their communities. PeacePlayers International currently operates year-round programs in South Africa, Northern Ireland, Israel and the West Bank, and Cyprus.</p>','<p><strong>MISSION</strong> To unite, educate and inspire young people in divided communities through basketball.<br /><br /> <strong>VISION</strong> Individual connections creating a more peaceful world.<br /><br /> Unifying Principles<br /><br /> Bridging Divides<br /><br /> Implementing consistent, year-round sports activities that bring together children from opposite sides of religious, ethnic and cultural divides to develop friendship and mutual respect.<br /><br /> Helping marginalized communities developed constructive outlets and positive role models for their youth, strengthening the capacity of the disenfranchised in support of sustainable peace.<br /><br /> Developing Leaders<br /><br /> Training and developing young adults from local communities to work together as coaches, mentors and leaders of peacebuilding efforts in their own communities.<br /><br /> Maintaining diverse and balanced leadership at all levels, including staff, board, volunteers and partners.<br /><br /> Changing Perceptions<br /><br /> Operating first-class sports activities not for the purpose of training top athletes, but as a tool to unite, educate and inspire.<br /><br /> Driving concrete, measurable changes in both the attitudes and behaviors of participants and communities and demonstrating these results to a global audience.<br /><br /></p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVNFe0YmUJY&list=UUdSu0WwgWRz4BSd9xnyVrfw&index=19',9,1,0,'@peaceplayers','facebook.com/peaceplayersintl','2013-05-15 16:47:56','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'peaceplayers-international',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(149,'Rancho Coastal Humane Society','389 Requeza Street','Encnitias','CA',92024,'www.rchumanesociety.org','95-2151583','<p>Rancho Coastal Humane Society (RCHS) was formed in 1960 by a group of hardworking volunteers, led by animal lover Maria K. Lloyd. The goal was and continues to be to care for the homeless animal population of San Diego County and to educate the public about pet over-population and responsible companion animal care.</p>','<p>In the nearly 50 years since our inception, RCHS has grown from a small facility run by volunteers to a professionally managed humane society that provides quality shelter care, adoption services, education programs and an animal safehouse program for the survivors of domestic violence.<br /><br /> The Rancho Coastal Humane Society is a non-profit, 501(c)3, charitable organization. We are a private animal shelter solely funded by donations from supporters and grants.<br /><br /> <strong>Adoptions</strong><br /><br /> One of RCHS\' main goals is the adoption of animals to permanent, loving homes. RCHS\' adoption process is tailored to find the best match between pets and people. After finding the perfect match, we help prospective adopters learn about health care, nutrition requirements, grooming, exercise, responsible pet ownership, socialization and the importance of the human/animal bond.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sE63eqR5qas&feature=player_profilepage',1,0,0,'','https://www.facebook.com/rchumane','2013-05-15 18:18:57','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'rancho-coastal-humane-society',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(150,'Public Campaign','1133 19th St. NW, 9th Floor','Washington','DC',20036,'www.publicampaign.org','52-2003442','<p>Public Campaign is a non-profit, non-partisan organization dedicated to sweeping campaign reform that aims to dramatically reduce the role of big special interest money in American politics. Public Campaign is laying the foundation for reform by working with a broad range of organizations, including local community groups, around the country that are fighting for change and national organizations whose members are not fairly represented under the current campaign finance system. Together we are building a network of national and state-based efforts to create a powerful national force for federal and state campaign reform.</p>','<p>For sixteen years, Public Campaign has been a leading organization in national efforts to combat the big-money interest funding of American political campaigns. We expose the inequities and damaging consequences of the current campaign fundraising system and educate the public about the democratic promise inherent in robust publicly financed campaign systems based on small donor matching. Public Campaign works closely with the separate Public Campaign Action Fund (PCAF), a 501(c)(4) organization.<br /><br /> We have worked with state activists across the country, most notably in Arizona, Connecticut, and Maine, to generate public enthusiasm for local models of Fair Elections&mdash;systems of publicly financed candidate campaigns. Under this policy, candidates may choose to run a financially competitive campaign utilizing only a combination of small contributions and money from a public fund. In 2006, we expanded this conversation to the national level while our sister organization, PCAF, worked on a new initiative to win publicly financed Congressional elections.<br /><br /> Following the Citizens United court decision and the 2010 elections, we refocused our efforts and committed increased resources to deepening anti-big money coalition efforts that exposed the damage caused by pay-to-play politics on social, economic, and environmental policy making. These efforts intensified in 2012 as more and more groups new to the issue sought our advice and partnership. They reached out to us based on their shared recognition that progress on their policy goals would be virtually impossible unless authentically democratic electoral and governing practices were restored.<br /><br /> At the urging of such groups, as well as our own recognition of the need for more focused outreach to grassroots activists who want to work on this issue, we are rolling out a unique training program &ndash; building a new generation of Fair Elections proponents through a carefully designed and tested curriculum we will share across multiple platforms, from conference workshops to do-it-yourself on-line training. Thus, while remaining lean and nimble, we will be doing our utmost to deepen and expand the Fair Elections movement across the country.<br /><br /> The campaign cash bacchanal of 2012 seems to have left the country with an enduring sense of regret and a growing hunger for the democracy we thought we had. As a consequence, and, as we hope this proposal has demonstrated, we see unique opportunities converging to build a movement powerful enough to put people back in &ndash; and take big money out of &ndash; the election process. Our sixteen years of focused experience in making the case and building power has prepared us for this moment.</p>','https://www.youtube.com/publicampaign',1,0,0,'@Publicampaign','','2013-05-15 19:00:32','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'public-campaign',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(151,'Mission Without Borders','711 Daily Dr, Suite 120','Camarillo','CA',93010,'www.mwb.org','77-0292572','<p>MWB is a 50-year old organization which provides Relief &amp; Development services to 33,000 children, 9,000 rural households, and 150,000 urban seniors in Europe&rsquo;s six poorest, former-Communist, countries. These are FORGOTTON PEOPLE IN FORGOTTON COUNTRIES.<br /><br /> With the fall of the Iron Curtain, thousands of abandoned and orphaned children, seniors, and rural poor were left with no social net to establish self-sufficiency. As the world&rsquo;s television cameras moved to other parts of the world, Mission Without Borders remained, building a local network of over 4,000 volunteers across Eastern Europe.</p>','<p>OUR MOST POPULAR PROGRAMS ARE: 1. Child Sponsorship: $25 per month supports one needy child in a home or orphanage. 2. Family Sponsorship: $100 per month supports one entire family through our F2F Program. The goal is hope and economic self-sustainability. 3. Community Centers: $14,460 per year ($1,205/month) supports a complete Community Center in one desperately-poor community. This program is perfect for groups or companies.<br /><br /> OUR PARTNERS IN SERVICE: We&rsquo;re the USA Partner of an 11-country consortium (USA, UK, Netherlands, Belgium, Canada, Norway, Germany, Switzerland, Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa) which serves: Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Moldova, Romania and the Ukraine.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S0Nspsv6Nck',6,0,0,'','https://www.facebook.com/mwbus','2013-05-16 15:51:04','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'mission-without-borders',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(152,'Special Olympics Arizona','2100 South 75th Avenue','Phoenix','Arizona',85043,'www.SpecialOlympicsArizona.org','86-0307564','<p>The mission of Special Olympics is to provide year-round sports training and athletic competition in a variety of Olympic-type sports for children and adults with intellectual disabilities, giving them continuing opportunities to develop physical fitness, demonstrate courage, experience joy and participate in a sharing of gifts, skills and friendship with their families, other Special Olympics athletes and the community.</p>','<p>Special Olympics Arizona Goal<br /><br /> Special Olympics Arizona\'s (SOAZ) goal is to empower the over 180,000 Arizonans with intellectual disabilities to be healthy, productive, and respected members of society through SOAZ\'s year-round sports training, competitions and support programs. <br /><br /> Special Olympics Athletes<br /><br /> For people with intellectual disabilities, Special Olympics is often the only place where they have an opportunity to participate in their communities and develop belief in themselves. For athletes, Special Olympics sports provide a gateway to empowerment, competence, acceptance and joy. The lessons learned in Special Olympics also impact their life skills. Sports training enhances focus and gives participants a structure for learning important lessons about perseverance, endurance and setting goals. Many people are surprised to know, more than half of adult Special Olympics athletes in the United States are employed, versus 10 percent of intellectually disabled persons who do not participate in Special Olympics.</p>','http://youtu.be/wvg47dojJRk',5,0,0,'SOArizona','SpecialOlympicsArizona','2013-05-16 17:05:18','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'special-olympics-arizona',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(153,'Regional Food Bank of Oklahoma','3355 S. Purdue, PO Box 270968','Oklahoma City','OK',73137,'www.regionalfoodbank.org','73-11000380','<p>\"Fighting Hunger...Feeding Hope\"</p>','<p>The Regional Food Bank of Oklahoma is the state&rsquo;s largest hunger relief organization. The nonprofit provides enough food to feed more than 90,000 hungry Oklahomans each week through a network of more than 1,000 schools and charitable feeding programs in 53 central and western Oklahoma counties. Since its inception in 1980, the Regional Food Bank has distributed more than 470 million pounds of food to feed Oklahoma&rsquo;s hungry. With administrative and fundraising costs below 4 percent, the Regional Food Bank can return five equivalent meals for every dollar donated. <br /><br />For more information, visit http://www.regionalfoodbank.org; find us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/regionalfoodbank or follow us on Twitter at www.twitter.com/rfbo.</p>','http://youtu.be/D36-_z1daVU',8,1,0,'www.twitter.com/rfbo','www.facebook.com/regionalfoodbank','2013-05-16 17:11:15','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'regional-food-bank-of-oklahoma',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(154,'Prevent Cancer Foundation','1600 Duke Street, Suite 500','Alexandria','VA',22314,'preventcancer.org','52-1429544','<p>The mission of the Prevent Cancer Foundation is saving lives through cancer prevention and early detection.</p>','<p>When the Prevent Cancer Foundation was started in 1985, the concept of cancer prevention and early detection was not widely embraced by the medical community or the general public. Today, cancer prevention and early detection is at the forefront of reducing cancer diagnoses and death. We have played a key role in changing this perception. The Prevent Cancer Foundation is the only U.S. nonprofit organization solely devoted to cancer prevention and early detection. The Foundation focuses its resources on cancers such as breast, cervical, colorectal, lung, oral, prostate, skin and testicular that can be prevented through lifestyle changes or early detection and treatment. In addition to these 8 cancers, there are many other preventable cancers like anal, endometrial, head and neck, oral, penile, throat and vulvar cancers. The Foundation has invested $130 million in research, education, advocacy and community outreach programs in support of our mission of saving lives through cancer prevention and early detection.</p>','http://youtu.be/QkBF3YNoSWQ',5,0,0,'@preventcancer','https://www.facebook.com/preventcancer','2013-05-17 15:07:41','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'prevent-cancer-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(155,'Shoes That Fit','1420 N. Claremont Blvd., Suite 204A','Claremont','CA',91711,'www.shoesthatfit.org','95-4425565','<p>Shoes That Fit is a national children\'s charity with the simple mission of providing new shoes to children in need so they can attend school in comfort and with dignity, better prepared to learn and play. New shoes that fit allow children to fit in with their peers, participate in outdoor activity and concentrate on their schoolwork rather than their circumstances. Our national office based in Claremont, CA supports volunteer chapters in 42 states across the country providing new shoes to children in need at more than 1,600 schools. Since our founding in 1992, more than 1 million pairs of new shoes and other items have been donated to children in need through our programs.</p>','<p>Shoes That Fit is a a unique nonprofit that has found a simple solution to an overwhelming problem. We provide new shoes to children in need thereby removing one of the most visibile signs of poverty. Our approach allows kids to concentrate on being kids and students instead of focusing on their circumstances. We match volunteers with schools in their own community that have children in need. Shoes That Fit volunteers are businesses, faith-based organizations, civic groups or groups of friends. These form the basis for our network of volunteers. Once the volunteer group decides how how many children they\'d like to help, school staff identify and measure that same number of children for proper size and fit with materials Shoes That Fit provides. This information allows our volunteers to buy exactly what each child needs and deliver the shoes to the school.</p>','http://youtu.be/TBo83G-feDs',9,0,0,'https://twitter.com/ShoesThatFit','https://www.facebook.com/ShoesThatFitNonProfit?ref=tn_tnmn','2013-05-17 18:16:07','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'shoes-that-fit',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(156,'Children\'s Hunger Fund','13931 Balboa Blvd','Sylmar','CA',91342,'www.ChildrensHungerFund.org','95-4335462','<p>Our mission is to deliver hope to suffering children by equipping local churches for Gospel-centered mercy ministry.</p>','<p>Since 1991, 99% of CHF&rsquo;s total contributions&mdash;over 1 billion dollars in food and other aid&mdash;have been distributed through programs serving more than 20 million children across America and around the world.<br /><br /> Through strategic partnerships in targeted communities, Children\'s Hunger Fund works to improve the lives of poor children and their families comprehensively, meeting their physical, emotional, and spiritual needs.<br /><br /> Through the following programs and projects, CHF provides ongoing help to the helpless.<br /><br /> &bull; Home Delivery of Food<br /> &bull; Emergency Feeding Campaigns<br /> &bull; Medical Clinics (Mobile and Permanent)<br /> &bull; Orphan Homes<br /> &bull; Discipleship<br /> &bull; Job Training <br /> &bull; Disaster Relief<br /> &bull; Clean Water<br /> &bull; Community Development<br /> &bull; Farming Training and Support<br /><br /> Children\'s Hunger Fund\'s strategies are most vividly exhibited in our Mercy Networks&reg;. These indigenously led groupings of local churches work tirelessly to care for poor children and families in their communities. Using CHF\'s Food Pak&reg; as a relationship building tool, trained volunteers bring food directly to the homes of suffering children and work to affect positive change in their lives.</p>','http://youtu.be/5We5Qr8bQMs',7,1,1,'@ServeAChild','https://www.facebook.com/ChildrensHungerFund?ref=ts&fref=ts','2013-05-20 22:57:16','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'children-s-hunger-fund',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(157,'East-West Ministries International','2001 W. Plano Pkwy., Suite 3000','Plano','Texas',75075,'http://www.eastwest.org/','75-2486132','<p>East-West exists to mobilize the body of Christ to evangelize the lost and equip local believers to multiply disciples and healthy churches among unreached peoples and/or in restricted access communities.</p>','<p>SPIRIT-LED AND EMPOWERED<br /><br /> Depending solely upon the leading and power of the Holy Spirit and highly valuing the power of personal and group prayer<br /><br /> ORGANIZATIONAL EXCELLENCE<br /> Pursuing servant leadership and faithful stewardship in a Biblically healthy organization<br /><br /> INTENTIONAL COMMUNITY<br /> Developing authentic relationships that move us toward spiritual maturity and regularly praying for our missionaries and one another<br /><br /> GRACE-ORIENTED<br /> Extending God&rsquo;s grace through our lives, our relationships, and our ministry<br /> How We Serve: Guiding Principles<br /><br /> EMPOWERING LOCAL LEADERS<br /> Equipping indigenous leaders for ministry that is culturally relevant and easily reproducible<br /><br /> INNOVATIVE AND PIONEERING<br /> Leading a ministry with prayerful flexibility, creativity, and courage<br /><br /> KINGDOM AGENDA<br /> Honoring Jesus Christ by prayerfully and aggressively pursuing His Kingdom agenda through partnerships and collaboration<br /><br /> CHURCH-FOCUSED<br /> Mobilizing and multiplying the church to fulfill its mandate to bring the gospel to the world</p>','http://youtu.be/_gxICOk_oNY',7,0,0,'@ewmi','https://www.facebook.com/ewministries','2013-05-21 20:13:57','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'east-west-ministries-international',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(158,'Operation USA','7421 Beverly Blvd, PH','Los Angeles','CA',90036,'www.OpUSA.org','95-3504080','<p>Operation USA helps communities alleviate the effects of disasters, disease and endemic poverty by providing privately-funded relief, reconstruction and development aid throughout the world. We offer material and financial assistance to community-based organizations that promote sustainable development, leadership and capacity building, income generating activities, education, health services, and advocacy on behalf of vulnerable people.</p>','<p>Since 1979, Operation USA has worked in more than 100 countries&mdash;delivering over $400 million in aid for relief and development projects around the world.<br /><br /> Operation USA is a hands-on agency&mdash;with a small, dedicated staff overseeing our projects and disaster response work. Free of the bureaucracy of a larger organization, creative solutions are encouraged to respond to real needs, in real time. 100% privately-funded, Operation USA works without any government support&mdash;or the constraints that support may bring. Founding Board member Julie Andrews says, &ldquo;Operation USA is the little ship that gets in the harbor where the big ships cannot go.&rdquo; <br /><br /> In most cases, the effects of disasters are not limited by time. Years after a disaster has abated, communities are still frequently in need of assistance. Dedicated to rebuilding with commitment, Operation USA stays in the field long after many others leave. Long-term projects focus on education, health and community-based projects that help to rebuild lives and livelihoods.</p>','http://youtu.be/OwXdoICxxFc',6,0,0,'@OperationUSA','www.Facebook.com/OperationUSA','2013-05-22 16:58:36','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'operation-usa',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(159,'Soles4Souls','319 Martingale Drive','Old Hickory','TN',37138,'www.soles4souls.org','20-4023482','<p>Soles4Souls is a global not-for-profit institution dedicated to fighting the devastating impact and perpetuation of poverty. The organization advances its anti-poverty mission by collecting new and used shoes and clothes from individuals, schools, faith based institutions, civic organizations and corporate partners, then distributing those shoes and clothes both via direct donations to people in need and by provisioning qualified micro-enterprise programs designed to create jobs in poor and disadvantaged communities.</p>','<p>Soles4Souls distributes shoes and clothing in two ways. Most new items collected primarily from corporations and retailers are given directly to people in need, both in the U.S. and overseas. The organization has relationships with several of the world&rsquo;s leading apparel brands, which provides Soles4Souls with new but non-marketable overstocks, returns, discontinued models and other shoes or clothing items.<br /><br /> At the same time, Soles4Souls receives millions of articles of used shoes and clothing that have been collected by individuals, schools, faith-based institutions, civic organizations and corporate partners. After sorting items in its national warehouse system, Soles4Souls typically sells the used shoes and clothing, as well as some new items allocated by manufacturers, to carefully selected micro-enterprise organizations. These both private and non-profit companies are contracted to provide shipping, financing, inventory, training and other support to ultra-small businesses in countries like Haiti where there are virtually no jobs to generate personal income.<br /><br /> Through the collection and sale of used (and new) clothing and shoes, Soles4Souls helps create self-sustaining jobs that generate desperately needed revenues throughout those communities. The sale of footwear and apparel to support micro-jobs also provides the majority of funding to sustain Soles4Souls operations and further expand its donations of new shoes and clothing.</p>','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JTi0TuZAlGA',8,1,0,'twitter.com/soles4souls','facebook.com/giveshoes','2013-05-23 16:10:23','2013-09-04 18:56:05',NULL,'soles4souls',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(160,'Rosie\'s Place','889 Harrison Avenue','Boston','MA',2118,'www.rosiesplace.org','04-2582187','<p>The mission of Rosie&rsquo;s Place is to provide a safe and nurturing environment for poor and homeless women to maintain their dignity, seek opportunity and find security in their lives.</p>','<p>Since 1974 poor and homeless women have found an oasis of hope and nourishment at Rosie&rsquo;s Place. The mission of Rosie&rsquo;s Place is to help women maintain their dignity, seek opportunity and find security in their lives.<br /><br /> Many of the women we assist are working and in housing but simply can&rsquo;t make ends meet. Some are newly homeless, while others women have been living on the streets for years. We serve women as young as 18 and as old as 80. Approximately one-third of our guests have children. Rosie\'s Place serves guests from a wide variety of ethnic groups, with the majority being African American, Hispanic, Haitian, or White. Some of our guests are living with HIV/AIDS or have hidden disabilities such as addiction or mental illnesses that prevent them from effectively integrating into society. <br /><br /> With the help of people who believe change is possible and share our vision of justice, Rosie&rsquo;s Place has accomplished amazing things, both big and small. Rosie&rsquo;s Place continues to rely solely on the enthusiasm of our volunteers and the generous support of individuals, foundations, and corporations. We do not accept funding from the city, state or federal governments or the United Way. Thanks to these generous donations, 88 cents of every dollar raised goes directly to services for women and their children.</p>','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8KskNi-s0Po',8,0,0,'@rosiesplace','https://www.facebook.com/pages/Rosies-Place/65796105803','2013-05-23 17:14:23','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'rosie-s-place',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(162,'Hope Strengthens Foundation','80 Emerson Road','Walpole','MA',2032,'www.hopestrengthens.org',' 27-1653356','<p>Hope Strengthens Foundation helps provide support to individuals and families whose lives have been burdened due to circumstances extending from illness or tragedy.</p>','<p>Hope Strengthens Foundation is a 501(c)(3) public charity founded by long-time friends James Fahey and Jacob Ferreira in 2010. Its roots were established when a mutual friend, Joseph Merry, valiantly battled against and beat cancer. Joe&rsquo;s drive towards remission was centered in two simple words; Hope Strengthens. <br /><br /> That motto not only drove Joe, it inspired his family and friends to come together as a community. In an effort to support him, many members of his community organized a fundraiser to ensure that Joe could focus all his energy on his recovery and rest easy knowing his expenses would be covered while out of work. <br /><br /> Today, Hope Strengthens Foundation exists because of Joe&rsquo;s strength and the unyielding support that can be found in communities all across our country.</p>','',5,0,0,'@hopestrengthens','www.facebook.com/hopestrengthens','2013-05-28 03:45:34','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'hope-strengthens-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(163,'Revere Beach Partnership','150 Beach Street','Revere','MA',2151,'www.reverebeachpartnership.com','05-565298','<p>To continue the heritage of Revere Beach as a nearby retreat for New England families; to preserve the beach&rsquo;s unique historic and natural assets; to strengthen the beach as an asset to our community by the development of programs and partnerships within the community that further this goal and the overall well-being of our community; to plan and oversee the continued improvement of Revere Beach.</p>','<p>Revere Beach Partnership is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization that was established in 2001. Its purpose is to continue the heritage of Revere Beach as a nearby retreat for New England families; to preserve the beach&rsquo;s unique historic and natural assets; to strengthen the beach as an asset to our community by the development of programs and partnerships within the community that further this goal and the overall well-being of our community; to plan and oversee the continued improvement of Revere Beach. The Partnership consists of an executive director, a volunteer Board of Directors, and other volunteers that share a love for Revere Beach.<br /><br /> The main event of the organization is the Revere Beach National Sand Sculpting Festival, now in its 10th year. Funds raised during the event are used to offset the expenses of the festival and to fund the organization&rsquo;s efforts throughout the remainder of the year including establishing a capital plan which will allow the organization to fund major improvement projects that aim to strengthen the fabric of the Revere Beach community.</p>','',4,0,0,'','https://www.facebook.com/VisitRevereBeach','2013-05-29 13:54:25','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'revere-beach-partnership',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(164,'RIVERKEEPER','20 Secor Road','Ossinning','New York',10562,'www.riverkeeper.org','EIN: 13-3204621','<p>Riverkeeper is a member-supported watchdog organization dedicated to defending the Hudson River and its tributaries and protecting the drinking water supply of nine million New York City and Hudson Valley residents.<br /><br /> For more than 45 years Riverkeeper has been New York&rsquo;s clean water advocate. We have helped to establish globally recognized standards for waterway and watershed protection and serve as the model and mentor for the growing Waterkeeper movement that includes nearly 200 Keeper programs across the country and around the globe</p>','<p><strong>Our Mission</strong><br /><br /> To protect the environmental, recreational and commercial integrity of the Hudson River and its tributaries, and safeguard the drinking water of nine million New York City and Hudson Valley residents.<br /><br /> <strong>Our Vision</strong><br /><br /> The Hudson River and the NYC Watershed are healthy ecosystems teeming with life. Residents and visitors care for and help protect these ecosystems, which provide safe drinking water and abundant opportunities for swimming, fishing, boating and other recreational activities.<br /><br /> <strong>Our Story</strong><br /><br /> We began as the Hudson River Fisherman\'s Association and, more than 40 years later, we are New York&rsquo;s clean water advocate, having helped set worldwide standards for waterway and watershed protection and serving as the model for more than 190 Keeper programs around the globe.Learn More<br /><br /> <strong>Our Methods</strong><br /><br /> Riverkeeper is the public&rsquo;s investigator, scientist, lawyer, lobbyist and public relations agent for the Hudson River. We have investigated and brought to justice hundreds of environmental lawbreakers as we protect and restore the Hudson River, safeguard New York&rsquo;s drinking water, and fight to replace the Indian Point nuclear power plant with safe renewable energy</p>','http://youtu.be/Lpq87ggqEMU',4,0,0,'@riverkeeper_ny','https://www.facebook.com/HudsonRiverkeeper?fref=ts','2013-05-30 14:04:03','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'riverkeeper',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(165,'The Glaucoma Foundation','80 Maiden Lane, Suite 700','New York','NY',10038,'www.glaucomafoundation.org','13-3174839','<p>The mission of The Glaucoma Foundation is to develop a cure for glaucoma through innovative research and collaboration.</p>','<p>The Glaucoma Foundation is one of the premier not-for-profit organizations dedicated to eradicating blindness from glaucoma through vital research and education.<br /><br /> The Foundation works to encourage and support basic and applied research in glaucoma, to gain and disseminate new information about the causes and treatment of glaucoma, and to further efforts to identify and develop novel approaches to preserve visual function and reverse blindness caused by glaucoma. <br /><br /> &bull; Over the past 10 years The Foundation&rsquo;s Grant-in-Aid Program has awarded more than $3 million dollars in seed money for cutting-edge research projects. Preliminary data from these projects have frequently been used to support proposals for larger grants from entities such as the National Institutes of Health. <br /><br /> &bull; Since 1994 The Glaucoma Foundation&rsquo;s interdisciplinary Annual International Scientific Think Tank has brought together some of the world&rsquo;s top scientists and clinicians. These gatherings have significantly impacted setting the course to find new treatments and cures for glaucoma. <br /><br /> &bull; Headquartered in New York, TGF serves patients across the globe through its website, on-line support groups and local chapters in Greater Chicago, Long Island (NY), Dallas/Fort Worth (TX), Central New York, San Francisco Bay Area, Madison (WI), Palm Beach Gardens (FL), New England, and New York City. <br /><br /> &bull; The organization&rsquo;s &ldquo;Eye to Eye&rdquo; newsletter keeps more than 30,000 households worldwide informed about research news and other developments, and includes such informative features as &ldquo;Doctor, I Have A Question.&rdquo;</p>','',5,0,0,'@tgf_glaucoma','the.glaucoma.foundation','2013-05-30 15:52:19','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'the-glaucoma-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(166,'The LAM Foundation','4015 Executive Park Dr, Suite 320','Cincinnati','OH',45241,'thelamfoundation.org','','<p>The LAM Foundation urgently seeks safe and effective treatment, and ultimately a cure, for lymphangioleiomyomatosis through advocacy and the funding of promising research. We are dedicated to serving the scientific, medical and patient communities by offering information, resources and a worldwide network of hope and support.</p>','<p>The LAM Foundation, a 501(c)(3), was established for the purpose of funding research and education related to an extremely rare disease called lymphangioleiomyomatosis (LAM). This progressive and frequently fatal disease, which scientists have determined to be a systemic neoplasm that results in cystic destruction of the lung, affects women almost exclusively, primarily in their childbearing years. Scientists estimate that there are as many as 300,000 women with LAM who are currently undiagnosed or misdiagnosed.<br /><br /> Three primary goals for the Foundation:<br /><br /> Patient Services - The Foundation conducted the first-ever LAM patient/family conference in 1997. Now this annual conference, the International LAM Research Conference (LAMposium), offers a three day, dual-track meeting for the LAM scientific and patient communities. The Foundation also provides an extraordinary network of support to women with LAM worldwide through the LAM Liaison program, printed materials, community forums, telephone calls, and emails.<br /> Research - The LAM Foundation research program has produced 91 grant awards to LAM investigators, totaling $9.3 million. With adequate research funding, we believe a cure for this disease will be uncovered through scientific investigation.<br /> LAM Clinics - To improve the care and treatment of all LAM patients, The LAM Foundation has established 26 LAM Clinics throughout the US. Each clinic is strategically positioned based on the number of patients in a geographic area combined with physicians who have an interest in LAM at institutions that value research in rare diseases.</p>','',5,0,0,'','The LAM Foundation','2013-05-30 17:42:46','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'the-lam-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(167,'National Military Family Association','2500 N. Van Dorn Street, Suite 102','Alexandria','VA',22302,'www.MilitaryFamily.org','52-0899384','<p>To fight for benefits and programs that strengthen and protect Uniformed Services families and reflect the Nation&rsquo;s respect for their service.</p>','','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zHArPP0ddm4',1,0,0,'@military_family','https://www.facebook.com/militaryfamily','2013-06-03 19:41:23','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'national-military-family-association',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(168,'Perkins Deafblind Program','175 North Beacon St','Watertown','Massachusetts',2472,'http://www.perkins.org','042-103616','<p>Perkins is an innovative leader in serving people with visual impairments. Strong leadership from both staff and the Board of Trustees has created a legacy of education and discovery. We are always questioning how to best serve our students in the classroom, in the community and around the world.</p>','<p>Perkins is an innovative leader in serving people with visual impairments. Strong leadership from both staff and the Board of Trustees has created a legacy of education and discovery. We are always questioning how to best serve our students in the classroom, in the community and around the world.<br /><br /> Perkins is a unique and exciting place, but don&rsquo;t take our word for it.<br /><br /> While Perkins is proud of all that has been achieved since 1832, we believe there is still much work to be done.<br /><br /> Today, in New England, around the nation and throughout the world, many people who are visually impaired are not receiving the services they need to be healthy and independent. Together we can raise awareness. <br /><br /> Today, the challenge of preparing students to become independent is more complex than ever. Together we can support the changing needs of our students. <br /><br /> Today, in the developing world, 85% of children with disabilities receive no education.Together we can take the next steps to building a brighter future for these children.<br /><br /> Today, many members of the growing population of seniors in this country are losing their sight. Also thanks to medical advances, more premature babies are surviving but may face serious problems with vision and hearing. As the need for our services increases, the Perkins family must work even harder.<br /><br /> Together we can prove that at Perkins, all we see is possibility, today and tomorrow.</p>','',3,0,0,'@Perkins_School','https://www.facebook.com/OfficialPerkins','2013-06-08 01:54:18','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'perkins-deafblind-program',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(170,'International Rhino Foundation','201 Main Street, Suite 2600','Fort Worth','Texas',76102,'www.rhinos.org','','<p>We are dedicated to the survival of the world\'s rhino species through conservation and research.</p>','<p>More than 30 years ago, Zimbabwe&rsquo;s black rhino population was decreasing at an alarming rate from intense, organized poaching. In response, a group of concerned individuals and institutions founded the Black Rhino Foundation in 1989 to assist in the conservation of black rhinos in Zimbabwe through efforts in the wild and in captivity. In part because of the Black Rhino Foundation&rsquo;s support, poaching was virtually eliminated and Zimbabwe&rsquo; black rhino population began to stabilize. In most areas throughout the species&rsquo; range, numbers are now increasing. In 1993, recognizing that the escalating crisis facing all five rhino species was not receiving the attention it deserved, the Black Rhino Foundation expanded its mission and became the International Rhino Foundation (IRF). The International Rhino Foundation is dedicated to the survival of the world&rsquo;s rhino species through conservation and research. At the heart of IRF&rsquo;s vision is the belief that these magnificent species should endure for future generations, and that protecting rhinos ensures the survival of many other species that share their habitat, including people.<br /><br /> All five living rhino species (Black, White, Indian, Sumatran and Javan) are in terrible peril - from poaching, from forest loss and habitat conversion, and from human settlements encroaching on their habitats in Africa, Indonesia, and India. IRF works to protect particularly threatened rhino populations and their habitats in the wild, while also supporting management of and research on captive populations to improve the chances for long-term survival. IRF operates in situ programs in Asia and Africa targeted to the rhino species most in need of and most appropriate for intensive protection and management. These anti-poaching and protection programs also provide significant benefits for numerous other threatened species and for the entire ecosystems in which the animals live. In all our field programs, we work closely with local communities to ensure that those people living in closest proximity to rhinos, many of whom are also struggling as a result of poverty and environmental degradation, will serve as active partners in wildlife protection and will reap direct benefits from conservation efforts.<br /><br /> IRF&rsquo;s current major programs include: 1) Indonesia Rhino Protection Units, anti-poaching patrol units which protect Sumatran and Javan rhinos in the wild; 2) the Sumatran Rhino Sanctuary, a research and breeding center for Sumatran rhinos in Way Kambas National Park; 3) the Javan Rhino Study and Conservation Area, a program to expand the only viable habitat for Javan rhinos in the world by 4,000 hectares; 4) Indian Rhino Vision 2020, a program aimed at increasing the number of Indian rhinos and spreading the population out over more protected areas; 5) Zimbabwe Lowveld Rhino Conservation Program, which provides management, monitoring and veterinary interventions for black rhinos in Zimbabwe; and 6) Operation Stop Poaching Now, a campaign to provide training and equipment to anti-poaching units in Zimbabwe and South Africa. IRF also supports scientific research, regularly providing grants for work that is directly applicable to management, propagation and conservation of rhinoceros species in nature and in captivity.</p>','',4,0,0,'@RhinosIRF','International Rhino Foundation','2013-06-14 20:56:36','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'international-rhino-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(172,'Run Against Cancer Events (RACE)','One Marina Park Drive 14th Floor','Boston, ','MA',2210,'http://runagainstcancer.org/','','<p>kick-ass events to kick cancer&rsquo;s ass.</p>','<p>RACE &ndash; Run Against Cancer Events, Inc. produces kick-ass events to raise funds and awareness for charitable projects and organizations dedicated to kicking cancer&rsquo;s ass. We also manage Team RaceMenu, a grassroots racing program comprised of endurance athletes competing at all levels, from recreational to professional. Based in the heart of Boston, RACE is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization. If you would like more information, please drop us a line.</p>','http://youtu.be/Y3e4PmmPyO4',5,0,0,'','','2013-06-24 22:50:15','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'run-against-cancer-events-race',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(173,'Feeding America West Michigan Food Bank','864 West River Center Drive','Comstock Park','Michigan',49321,'https://www.feedingamericawestmichigan.org/','38-2439659','<p>Feeding America West Michigan Food Bank exists to ensure food is available to the hungry in our community.</p>','<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <w:WordDocument>\r\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\r\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\r\n  <w:TrackMoves/>\r\n  <w:TrackFormatting/>\r\n  <w:PunctuationKerning/>\r\n  <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/>\r\n  <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>\r\n  <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent>\r\n  <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>\r\n  <w:DoNotPromoteQF/>\r\n  <w:LidThemeOther>EN-US</w:LidThemeOther>\r\n  <w:LidThemeAsian>X-NONE</w:LidThemeAsian>\r\n  <w:LidThemeComplexScript>X-NONE</w:LidThemeComplexScript>\r\n  <w:Compatibility>\r\n   <w:BreakWrappedTables/>\r\n   <w:SnapToGridInCell/>\r\n   <w:WrapTextWithPunct/>\r\n   <w:UseAsianBreakRules/>\r\n   <w:DontGrowAutofit/>\r\n   <w:SplitPgBreakAndParaMark/>\r\n   <w:DontVertAlignCellWithSp/>\r\n   <w:DontBreakConstrainedForcedTables/>\r\n   <w:DontVertAlignInTxbx/>\r\n   <w:Word11KerningPairs/>\r\n   <w:CachedColBalance/>\r\n  </w:Compatibility>\r\n  <m:mathPr>\r\n   <m:mathFont m:val=\"Cambria Math\"/>\r\n   <m:brkBin m:val=\"before\"/>\r\n   <m:brkBinSub m:val=\"&#45;-\"/>\r\n   <m:smallFrac m:val=\"off\"/>\r\n   <m:dispDef/>\r\n   <m:lMargin m:val=\"0\"/>\r\n   <m:rMargin m:val=\"0\"/>\r\n   <m:defJc m:val=\"centerGroup\"/>\r\n   <m:wrapIndent m:val=\"1440\"/>\r\n   <m:intLim m:val=\"subSup\"/>\r\n   <m:naryLim m:val=\"undOvr\"/>\r\n  </m:mathPr></w:WordDocument>\r\n</xml><![endif]--></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">One of the nation&rsquo;s largest and most effective food banks, Feeding America West Michigan Food Bank reclaims edible surplus food from farmers, manufacturers, distributors and retailers. It stores, processes and distributes that food through more than 1,200 local food pantries and other hunger-relief agencies in 40 Michigan counties from the Indiana border through the Upper Peninsula. More than 100,000 West Michigan families rely on food from Feeding America West Michigan. For more information, visit </span><a href=\"http://www.feedingamericawestmichigan.org/\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">feedingamericawestmichigan.org</span></a><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">.</span></p>','http://youtu.be/V1sZnq_Jn-8',8,0,0,'@feedingwestmich','https://www.facebook.com/FeedingAmericaWestMichigan','2013-06-26 20:29:11','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'feeding-america-west-michigan-food-bank',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(175,'Womp 4 The Kids','N/A','New York','NY',10010,'http://womp4thekids.com/','','In a combined effort with our charity partners, it is our mission to inspire electronic music fans to support programs that directly improve the health, well-being and education of children.',NULL,'',9,0,0,'','','2013-07-05 05:11:46','2013-07-05 13:51:07',0,'womp-4-the-kids',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(176,'Good Sports, Inc','1515 Hancock Street, Suite 301','Quincy','MA',2169,'www.goodsports.org','75-3138664','<p>Good Sports is a non-profit organization dedicated to giving all kids the change to play by donating sports and fitness equipment to disadvantaged youth.</p>','<p>Good Sports helps lay the foundation for healthy, active lifestyles by providing athletic equipment, footwear and apparel to disadvantaged young people nationwide. By partnering with sporting goods manufacturers, Good Sports gets crucial equipment to kids who need it most, getting them in the game. Since 2003, Good Sports has provided more than $9 million worth of equipment to 1,150 youth programs, impacting more than 640,000 kids.</p>','http://vimeo.com/67819413',9,0,0,'@goodsportsinc','www.facebook.com/GSportsInc','2013-07-09 15:23:49','2013-07-16 18:35:41',0,'good-sports-inc',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(177,'The Foundation for Lee County Public Schools','2266 Second Street','Ft. Myers','FL',33901,'www.leeschoolfoundation.org','59-2637849','<p>The Foundation for Lee County Public Schools is a non-profit charitable education foundation which enhances and enriches the quality of public education for students and educators through programs, resources and experiences made possible through corporate, individual and educational partnerships. Some of our programs include Student Advocacy and Mentoring Partnership (STAMP), STEM@Work, ArtSpeak, Take Stock in Children, Dancing Classrooms, the Teacher Resource Center, Golden Apple Teacher Award Recognition, Collegium Quality Teacher Education, Classroom Grants, Anti-Bullying Initiative and more. Our goal is to help students achieve at their highest potential and equip educators with the resources they need to be the best.</p>','<p>Established in 1986, The Foundation for Lee County Public Schools works to increase the quality of public education so that every student can achieve at their highest level. We are the 9th largest school district in Florida and 40th largest in the United States. There are over 85,000 students in Lee County Public schools; more than 75% are on the free / reduced lunch program; 52% are a minority with English as a second language. Lee County has 1393 homeless students enrolled and about 1000 migrant students. Our students represent 159 countries and speak approximately 98 different languages.</p>','',3,0,0,'','https://www.facebook.com/?sk=welcome#!/TheFoundationforLeeCountyPublicSchools?fref=ts','2013-07-12 19:20:34','2013-07-16 18:44:37',0,'the-foundation-for-lee-county-public-schools',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(178,'AdMeTech Foundation','4 Longfellow Place, Suite 3802','Boston','MA',2114,'www.admetech.org','52-2079827','<p>AdMeTech Foundation is a non-profit organization dedicated to battling prostate cancer through the advancement of early detection. We aim to create \"Manograms\" (akin to mammograms) to improve early detection and treatment for the 1 in 6 men affected by prostate cancer.</p>','<p>MISSION AdMeTech provides international leadership and conducts ground-breaking programs in research, advocacy and education for the development of accurate diagnostic tools for early detection and minimally-invasive treatment of prostate cancer to. This technology will save lives, improve the quality of life in millions of men and reduce billions of dollars in health care costs. APPROACH To achieve these goals, AdMeTech has undertaken a public awareness campaign to recognize the prostate cancer crisis as a national priority and to increase public and private funding for research. Massachusetts General Court and Boston City Council both issued resolutions recognizing the AdMeTech Foundation for its efforts in research and awareness to improve early detection and treatment of prostate cancer.</p>','',5,0,0,'manogram','www.facebook.com/manogram','2013-07-17 18:36:30','2013-07-24 15:01:39',0,'admetech-foundation',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(180,'Celebrity Series of Boston','20 Park Plaza Suite 1032','Boston','MA',2116,'www.celebrityseries.org','','Celebrity Series of Boston presents world-class performing artists who inspire and enrich our community. ','We believe in the power of excellence and innovation in the performing arts to enrich life experience, transform lives, and build better communities. We envision a community of Greater Boston where the performing arts are a valued, lifelong, shared experience - on stages, in schools, in homes - everywhere.\r\n','',2,NULL,NULL,'@celebrityseries','https://www.facebook.com/celebrityseries?ref=hl','2013-07-24 16:42:15','2013-07-24 20:24:13',NULL,'celebrity-series-of-boston',1,'Stephanie Janes','sj@celebrityseries.org','617-598-3240'),(181,'Leukemia & Lymphoma Society','333 East Carson Street, Suite 441','Pittsburgh','PA',15219,'www.lls.org','13-5644916','<p>Cure leukemia, lymphoma, Hodgkin\'s disease adn myeloma an improve the quality of life of patients and their families.</p>','','',5,0,0,'https://twitter.com/LLSWPA','','2013-07-26 20:22:55','2013-07-29 20:48:43',0,'leukemia-lymphoma-society',1,'Courtney Wertz','courtney.wertz@lls.org','412-697-2873'),(182,'Islamic Relief USA','3655 Wheeler Ave.','Alexandria','VA',22304,'www.irusa.org','95-4453134','Islamic Relief USA strives to alleviate suffering, hunger, illiteracy, and diseases worldwide regardless of color, race, religion, or creed, and to provide aid in a compassionate and dignified manner. Islamic Relief USA aims to provide rapid relief in the event of human and natural disasters and to establish sustainable local development projects allowing communities to better help themselves.','Islamic Relief USA™ (IRUSA™) was founded in California in 1993 as a 501 (c)(3) tax exempt charity involved in international humanitarian relief efforts. IRUSA is a legally separate and independent member of a global family of collaborating relief organizations that share a common vision, mission, and family identity, and all of which use the term “Islamic Relief” as part of their organizational name.','',6,NULL,NULL,'','','2013-07-26 23:23:41','2013-07-29 17:32:13',NULL,'islamic-relief-usa',1,'Daud Mohmand','dmohmand@irusa.org','714-676-1285'),(183,'Habitat for Humanity Greater San Francisco','645 Harrison Street, Suite 201','San Francisco','CA',94107,'www.habitatgsf.org','94-3088881','<p>Habitat for Humanity Greater San Francisco partners with working families and the community to build affordable ownership homes in San Francisco, Marin, and the Peninsula.</p>','<p>Habitat Greater San Francisco provides a hand-up, not a hand-out for families in desperate need of improved living conditions. Our homeowners invest 500 hours of \"sweat equity\" to help build their own homes as well as additional time for homeowner workshops. Houses are sold to partner families at no profit and are financed with affordable, zero interest mortgages. With input from volunteers, partner homeowners, donors, community leaders and staff, Habitat Greater San Francisco&rsquo;s Board of Directors approved a plan to meet ambitious goals by 2020. Under the 2020 Vision, we plan to: &bull;Build 400 more homes in Marin, San Francisco and the Peninsula: several new developments have been proposed in all three counties served by the organization. &bull;Deepen our community impact by renovating 200 more homes and 50 neighborhood facilities, and helping more families to qualify for homeownership through financial skill-building programs. &bull;Leverage Habitat\'s highly visible brand to raise awareness of the local Habitat Greater San Francisco affiliate and stimulate more involvement through volunteerism and philanthropy. &bull;Dramatically increase revenue generation through fundraising, community support and a new Habitat ReStore.</p>','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uxMm8tHTZmM',8,0,0,'@habitatgsf','www.facebook.com/habitatgsf','2013-08-27 20:25:56','2013-08-27 20:42:45',0,'habitat-for-humanity-greater-san-francisco',1,'Jamin Sartor','jsartor@habitatgsf.org','415-625-1018'),(184,'Miles Against Melanoma','150 Medical Dr #6304','Boerne','TX',78006,'www.milesagainstmelanomasouthtexas.webs.com','35-2391462','To increase awareness of malignant melanoma and skin cancer through education, advocacy and research.\r\nTo advocate for detection and to obtain skin examinations.  We help people find dermatologists in their area as well.\r\nTo ease the burden and to provide support for melanoma patients, caregivers and medical professionals through financial aid that will ultimately bring a cure to melanoma.','Miles Against Melanoma is a national organization that began in 2010. Our mission is to provide the public with education regarding the extreme damaging effects of the sun and tanning devices.  Through MAM, we provide funding for awareness, education, advocacy and research for skin cancer, melanoma and cancers related to melanoma.  \r\n\r\nEach chapter is lead by someone who was affected by melanoma.  We are passionate about educating the public regarding melanoma. Each chapter designates to whom they wish to donate.  For example, for South Texas, we have designated the START Cancer Center in San Antonio TX as our choice of donation.  We have chapters in various cities in the United States.  Therefore, the money is being spread out across the US who are focusing on bringing a cure to melanoma.  Additionally, unlike many charities, our administrative costs are low because we are all volunteers.  Many of us have full time jobs, families and other life balances (such as the disease itself).  None of us, including the founder, takes pay or monetary incentive through the donations.\r\n\r\nYeah, we\'re passionate.','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G521a7XduY4',5,NULL,NULL,'MAMSTX','Miles Against Melanoma South Texas','2013-09-14 14:07:33','2013-09-16 21:45:26',NULL,'miles-against-melanoma',1,'Jaime Leeper','jaime.leepermamstx@gmail.com','210-724-4936'),(185,'test','asdasd','daasd','Indiana',12312,'123123','123','123','','',7,NULL,NULL,'','','2013-09-25 11:45:37','2013-09-25 11:45:37',NULL,'test',0,'asd da','ali123@gmail.com','');
